<HEAD>Sheriff's Department Makes Its Own Crack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Polk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> is making its own crack these days, having decided it is a safer and more efficient way to supply its undercover agents for sales to drug buyers. While most law enforcement agencies use crack confiscated during investigations for undercover operations, <LOCATION> Polk </LOCATION> officials decided they needed more than the `` very limited supply'' of crack they had on hand, a department report said. In addition, there were worries about impurities sometimes found in confiscated crack. Turning powder cocaine into crack cocaine requires a powdery base substance as well as the drug. Some dealers have been known to use Drano or other toxic chemicals as the base, sheriff's Lt. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Madden </PERSON> said recently. `` After reviewing all our options and checking with other agencies in the state that are taking an aggressive approach to crack, we felt the safest and most reliable way to handle these reverses would be use crack that was produced in a clean, controlled environment,'' the report said. <LOCATION> Polk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> deputies posing as drug dealers have routinely set up shop in known drug neighborhoods and sold crack to drug buyers in cars. Deputies have made more than 600 reverse-sting arrests since the campaign began in earnest last fall. The Sheriff's Office crack was made at the department by a supervisor in the drug unit who had gone over the fairly simple cooking procedure with technicians from the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION>. Baking powder was used as a base substance. The cooking session produced 11 ounces, enough to make several thousand pieces of crack in the size commonly sold on the street, officials said.
