<HEAD>Couples Can Take The Wedding Plunge Next To Lake Michigan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Looking for a unique setting to exchange vows? How about an old pier, complete with dramatic view of the city, a gentle lake breeze, and a couple of fishermen and joggers thrown in for charm? The city's <ORGANIZATION> Marriage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> offers the service at <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pier </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> as an alternative to the mundane civil ceremony at City Hall. The $ 10 price wo n't hurt the wallet much and the view is almost guaranteed to take the wedding party's breath away. `` A judge from <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> marries the couples. ... It's like getting married at the City Hall only you get married at lovely <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pier </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayman </PERSON>, who coordinates the weddings for the Department of Cultural Affairs. `` You can be as elaborate as you want, within reason,'' Ms. <PERSON> Wayman </PERSON> said Friday. `` I've seen six bridesmaids and flower girls'' at one wedding, she said. `` I've seen couples arrive by horse and carriage ... and a lot of people walk out just casually dressed. It runs the gamut.'' The pier, which once was bustling with Great Lakes' shippers, is frequented by athletes and anglers, so couples who marry there should be prepared for `` fishermen sitting right next to them ... and joggers jogging right by,'' Ms. <PERSON> Wayman </PERSON> said.
