<SECOND>PM-Burn Camp,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scarred Youngsters Get Week To Forget Their Burns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WONDER VALLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From a distance, there's no telling sign that the noisy children and teen-agers romping around a summer camp share the deep emotional and physical scars that accompany disfiguring burns. `` We try to give them a whole week to be free of their burn,'' said <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, who heads the special camp. It's called <LOCATION> Wonder </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ranch </LOCATION>, this secluded spot nestled in the <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> 200 miles southeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. This week 77 young burn survivors from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state frolicked in a swimming pool, rode ponies or cast a fishing line into a trout pond. `` If my mom would n't have taken me, I would have walked here,'' declared <PERSON> David </PERSON>, an 11-year-old enjoying the camp sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> Alisa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ruch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. `` The counselors are real cool. They treat you really nice.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, the foundation's executive director, described the camp as therapy to help fortify a burn victim's self-esteem. Most important, it lets them simply be kids free from a society too often repelled by the disfigurement of burns. There is one strict rule: No one can ask the children about their accident. `` That's why camp is so good for them _ they do n't have to deal with the accident,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>. `` We do n't want them reliving that.'' The children splashing in the pool on a hot summer morning played as if they never had endured painful skin grafts, worn an uncomfortable pressure garment to reduce swelling or been cruelly teased by peers. As <PERSON> Corky </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cecily </PERSON> splashed around, <PERSON> Corky </PERSON> stretched her scarred arm around <PERSON> Cecily </PERSON>'s back, proclaiming with a wide smile: `` We're friends. Mrs. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>'s husband, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> firefighter and foundation member, said there's little reluctance among these summer campers to test new experiences. `` They've been through so much pain, they'll try anything,'' <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said. The camp is rewarding for the volunteer counselors, mostly firefighters and their spouses. `` If you come up here for a week, you get enough hugs and kisses to last a year,'' said <PERSON> Nan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziegler </PERSON>, a nurse from <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. `` I love them. They are just little kids. They can forget what they look like,'' said <PERSON> Christen </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, a lifeguard from <LOCATION> Clovis </LOCATION>. `` I'm going to miss these kids.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said such a loving and accepting environment is n't typical for burn survivors Society is wary of burn victims, she said. Some gawk at a survivor's blistered and grafted skin, while others treat them like pariahs. She told of an incident of a restaurant owner asking a family to leave because the sight of their child, a burn victim, made his patrons uncomfortable. These experiences, along with the fact that many burn victims remain physically scarred for life, add up to a `` devastating'' psychological effect on the victims and their families, Mrs. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said. Easing such trauma is one of the foundation's goals. `` Now that -LRB- doctors -RRB- have solved the major medical problems and are able to keep them alive, they are now concentrating on the quality of life,'' she said. She estimated that 4,000 children are seriously burned in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> each year. All expenses for the children at the camp are paid by the foundation's fund-raising efforts and volunteer labor. Mrs. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> estimated that the week in <LOCATION> Wonder </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, which ends with a trip to <LOCATION> Disneyland </LOCATION>, cost the group about $ 100,000. Judging by the the children's grins, it appeared to be money well spent. `` Today and this week they are just kids,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>. She said she hopes the camp will help make them `` strong enough inside to take and handle the pressures their peers and adults give them.''
