<HEAD>Judge Prohibits Broadcast Of Colorized Version Of Huston Film</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> judge has prohibited a private television station from broadcasting a colorized version of `` Asphalt Jungle,'' a classic <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Huston </PERSON> film. The ruling Friday was the first of its kind in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Lawyers for the station, <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cinq </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Channel 5 -RRB-, said they would appeal. The colorized version of the 1950 film had been scheduled to run Sunday night. Judge <PERSON> Huguette </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Foyer </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Costil </PERSON> said the ruling affected all of <PERSON> Huston </PERSON>'s films. She noted that <PERSON> Huston </PERSON>, who died in August, opposed colorization and it was her duty to respect his will. The French <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Directors </ORGANIZATION>, which representives of <PERSON> Huston </PERSON>'s estate in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, had requested the injunction. `` We hope the first blow to the ` colorizers' will put a definitive stop to the surge of profiteering against creativity,'' the group said in a news release. <PERSON> Huston </PERSON> was so vehemently opposed to the tinting of his films that he attended a news conference denouncing the process not long before his death. A spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cinq </ORGANIZATION> said the station had aired colorized films previously, but none in which the authors had expressed their disapproval. French laws protecting the control by artists of their works are among the strongest in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> but it has no specific legislation dealing with colorization.
