<HEAD>Floods Kill 62 In East China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Floods and landslides caused by more than a week of heavy rains have killed 62 people in two provinces in eastern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, official reports said today. Six of the victims were children killed when a waterlogged school building collapsed in <LOCATION> Zhejiang </LOCATION> province's <LOCATION> Longquan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, the official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> reported. Heavy rains also fell this week in <LOCATION> Jiangxi </LOCATION> province on <LOCATION> Zhejiang </LOCATION>'s western border, causing a landslide that killed at least 17 people, the paper said. Reports today did not specify where or how the other 39 people died. The <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said 212,420 acres of farmland have been flooded and nearly 6,400 homes destroyed in <LOCATION> Zhejiang </LOCATION> since the rains began June 15. The rains in <LOCATION> Jiangxi </LOCATION> have flooded 568,000 acres of farmland and forced 14,000 people to flee their homes, the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Daily said. The report said four to 12 inches of rain fell on various parts of <LOCATION> Zhejiang </LOCATION> during a 10-day period ending Friday. <LOCATION> Zhejiang </LOCATION> normally receives about four inches of rain during the entire month of June. In <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the rainy season generally lasts until mid-July and more storms are forecast. Heavy storms last month in the same area of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> killed at least 131 people and heavily damaged crops.
