<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-History     06-25 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-History,0814</SECOND>
<HEAD>Under Glasnost, School History Exams Give Way To `Discussion'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Before glasnost, School No. 734 would have looked like this: 17-year-olds lined up in the hall in the summer heat, nervously awaiting a grilling on Soviet politics and history by a panel of teachers. That's what lanky, blond-haired <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> Predkov </PERSON> and his classmates at the school in eastern <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> had been expecting Friday. But last month, the head of Soviet education, <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yagodin </PERSON>, suddenly ordered the tests canceled. The reason: The final exams would have made students in the final year of school parrot material in textbooks now contradicted by the revelations of <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s drive for more openness in history and other areas. Instead, <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> and his 24 classmates, like 10th graders nationwide, were called into school for a three-hour ungraded `` discussion'' to gauge their knowledge of the past and awareness of problems facing the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> today. `` We want to be sure that the children can take part in discussions and are able to to voice their opinion anywhere,'' said their teacher, <PERSON> Vera </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zorich </PERSON>, 53. Despite that wish, most of the teen-age Muscovites who gathered at 9 a.m. Friday around four tables in a geography classroom said nothing during the ensuing `` discussion,'' despite repeated prompting from teachers. Some, however, aired views at odds with official ideology, and that presumably would have gotten them into trouble only a few years ago. One even joked about the Russian Revolution. <PERSON> Predkov </PERSON> stood up to say that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s program for `` perestroika,'' or economic and social restructuring, was not a natural consequence of the growth of Soviet socialism, and that people who say otherwise do so `` only because <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is the head of our party.'' `` We do n't have any rights. They're just words on paper,'' declared the son of a building engineer. Glasnost, <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> added, may allow more candor about history, but it does n't mean Soviet citizens are getting more information about current political problems. Another 17-year-old, wearing a thin black tie, said Soviets of all schools of thought, even `` fascists,'' should have the legal right to form their own political parties to challenge the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> heads. <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaztman </PERSON>, whose father works as a printer, made his classmates and teachers roar with laughter by telling this bittersweet joke about the legacy of the 1917 Russian Revolution: When the <ORGANIZATION> Bolsheviks </ORGANIZATION> seized power, <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> said, a <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> countess whose grandfather had been a 19th-century revolutionary summoned her maid to see what the shouting in the streets was about. `` Why, Madame, it's the revolution,'' the maid replied. `` Oh yes, grandfather dreamed of that. Tell me, what do they want?'' the countess asked. `` Why, they want a society where there are no more rich people.'' `` Strange,'' the countess replied. `` Grandfather wanted a society where there were no more poor people.'' `` Four years ago, maybe even a year ago, they would not have dared speak like that,'' a beaming Mrs. <PERSON> Zorich </PERSON> told a visiting reporter at the end of the meeting. In recent months, Soviet educators and official media have heaped scorn on the country's history textbooks, which have been outpaced by criticism in the glasnost-revitalized media about the crimes of dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and corruption and stagnation under <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>. `` Frankly, the books are of the ` hooray' type,'' said <PERSON> Tatyana </PERSON> <PERSON> Cherkashena </PERSON>, head of teaching methods in the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> neighborhood where School No. 734 is located. `` In our country, they say, everything is wonderful _ ` hooray.' Those who perished in the repressions, those who were imprisoned, are not even mentioned.'' A recent competition was held to select a new generation of Soviet textbooks, but it is uncertain whether they will be ready for the next school year in September. In the meantime, many Soviet teachers have been using articles published in the press as the basis for their history lessons. In years past, 10th grade students taking their final exams were given a slip of paper that bore two questions on history and civics. After a half-hour or more to prepare, they were called before a panel of teachers to speak and answer questions. In May, the principal of School 734, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tubelsky </PERSON>, was informed by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> that the customary year-end history exams for senior school pupils had been canceled. `` We were n't told about how to structure the discussions, so we decided to use the regular form of our history class, which the students would feel comfortable with,'' <PERSON> Tubelsky </PERSON> said. `` We need to change out textbooks,'' he added. `` They are based on a Stalinist conception that sees every event, every historical figure, through the dogma of class warfare.''
</TEXT>
