 The trustees of <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> voted Friday to merge the schools into a new entity, <ORGANIZATION> Clark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> is the financially troubled graduate school of the <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, a consortium of <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Spelman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Morehouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> and the Interdenominational Theological Center. The merger of <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, an undergraduate school, with the graduate school alters a nearly 60-year-old agreement among the seven historically <PERSON> black </PERSON> colleges to jointly finance maintenance, management and some academic programs. The new school will become the largest member of the consortium in terms of students and budget, with its annual budget placed at $ 30 million and 2,000 undergraduates and 1,000 graduate students. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> president <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, will be chief executive officer of the new institution.
