<HEAD>Suburban School First In Nation To Be Cited Under Asbestos Removal
Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Unaccredited workers botched asbestos removal at a high school and exposed students to cancer-causing fibers, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> charged Friday in its first enforcement of new regulations. The agency, which proposed a $ 5,000 fine, said 6,400 square feet of asbestos-containing floor tiles were improperly removed in February from a hallway at <ORGANIZATION> Thornton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Township </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in suburban <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>. Workers who were not accredited by the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> `` had sanded, chipped and cut the tiles, releasing clouds of dust containing asbestos,'' the agency said in a statement. The district overseeing the school in southwest suburban <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> failed to `` post signs and restrict the affected area to only those persons necessary to do tile removal and cleanup,'' the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. School officials have until July 11 to respond to the complaint. They can either seek an informal hearing with <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> or request a hearing before a federal administrative law judge, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. The school was closed Friday afternoon and officials could not be reached for comment. Ms. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said school officials did not know the tiles contained asbestos when the removal began, but suspected they might and ordered tests. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> called the complaint its first enforcement action nationwide under last year's Asbestos Hazard Emergency Response Act, which specifies procedures for removing asbestos in public and private elementary and secondary school