<SECOND>PM-Record Session,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arizona's `Walking Wounded' Surpass Record In Legislative Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two years of turmoil has taken a physical toll of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>'s lawmakers, who had to deal with the governor's time-consuming impeachment trial and face raising taxes $ 200 million just months before re-election bids Their current session set a record Friday as the longest in state history and they're far from finished with their business. `` I do n't think there's a member here who's not among the walking wounded,'' said House Minority Leader <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> Democrat. `` I'm just exhausted,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Usdane </PERSON>, a Republican from <LOCATION> Scottsdale </LOCATION>. `` It does n't feel good,'' said House Speaker <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON>. Friday was the 166th day of the session, but taxes, budgets, and about 50 other pieces of legislation are still not settled. And the lawmakers are operating on reduced pay, increased fatigue and, in some cases, worse health. In theory, legislative sessions are supposed to end by the Saturday of the week in which the 100th day falls. But the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> impeachment and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> trial of Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> took weeks out of each chamber's schedule this year. And the trauma started last year, when <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> faced off against a largely inexperienced set of legislative leaders. The stage was set in 1986, when then-Gov. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON> decided to run for president, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> decided to run for governor, Speaker <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sossaman </PERSON> ran for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Turley </PERSON> and Minority Leader <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON> retired. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> beat <PERSON> Barr </PERSON> in a rough Republican primary election and clashed repeatedly with the Republican-controlled legislature, until this year when the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ousted him on April 4. Now, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> loyalists are vowing revenge at the polls and Democrats are drooling at the prospect of increased numbers in both chambers. Many Republican incumbents simply are n't running for re-election, and others, such as <PERSON> Lane </PERSON>, face uphill election fights _ if they find the time to gather signatures on their nominating petitions before the June 30 deadline. Among the casualties: _ <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Runyan </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s majority whip, suffered a stroke while undergoing an operation and is confined to a wheelchair. He comes in only for key votes and will not seek re-election. _ <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Lunn </PERSON>, touted as one of the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>'s rising young stars, aggravated a pre-ulcerous condition and has decided to run for county supervisor instead of re-election. _ <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratliff </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> majority leader, suffered a heart attack and is retiring. _ Sterling Ridge, a <LOCATION> Glendale </LOCATION> Republican, also is retiring, citing health reasons. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, in his 16th year as a representative, said it was a very stressful session. `` It is the cumulative effect of the <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> administration and the kind of meanness that was there _ all of this madness.'' <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Democratic leader <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON> say <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> leaders bear some of the blame for allowing the session to continue drifting along. `` We've been putting things off and putting things off and putting things off,'' said <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON>, who estimated that 75 bills were languishing without debate while lawmakers cool their heels. `` To paraphrase <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Churchill </PERSON>, ` Never have so many worked for so long for so little,''' <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> said Thursday after <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> staged his second walkout of the week, spiking a tentative tax agreement. Other than <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s impeachment, lawmakers faced three major issues this year: air quality, indigent health care, and a state budget of about $ 3 billion. An air-quality bill is on the governor's desk, but there's no agreement on indigent health or budgets. Lawmakers draw salaries of $ 15,000 a year and extended their regular expense pay for 30 days beyond the normal 120-day limit, but since then they have been operating on reduced pay of $ 10 a day for Phoenix-area lawmakers and $ 20 a day for those from outside <LOCATION> Maricopa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Some grouchiness is a standard feature at every end-of-session crunch as lawmakers confront issues they avoided at first. But between the <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> trial's unheeled scars and the prospect of election fights ahead, lawmakers, lobbyists and others say things seem worse than usual. `` It just is n't as much fun,'' said <PERSON> Lunn </PERSON>. The previous record, 165 days, was set in 1976.
