anks. The tanks that blew up each contained 2.2 million gallons of gasoline. The tank farm was closed Friday by both company and government officials. <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nuevo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> press </ORGANIZATION> secretary, said the depot will remain closed at least until safety experts look it over and complete an investigation. The depot, one of two petroleum supply facilities in the area, contains 23 tanks that provide regular and unleaded gasoline and diesel fuel to gasoline stations and other users in the state. However, closure of the <LOCATION> Guadalupe </LOCATION> plant was not expected to have a major impact, because gasoline can be supplied from a huge refinery at <LOCATION> Cadereyta </LOCATION>, about 30 miles away. <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> said residents were being allowed to return to their homes late Friday although `` minuscule amounts'' of gasoline was still burning in one storage tank. Thick clouds of black smoke poured across the <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION> metropolitan area Friday evening. Many of the nearly 500 evacuees who packed one emergency shelter said Friday night they were fearful of going back. `` I'm too frightened to return now,'' said <PERSON> Sofia </PERSON> <PERSON> Villegas </PERSON>, a 41-year-old mother. `` We were so happy to be going home this morning, and then it happened all over again.'' `` I'm staying the night -LRB- here -RRB-,'' she added. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Guadalupe </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Adan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> said in an interview at one shelter that he would ask the state government to relocate the huge tank farm. Asked if he considered the depot a risk to the public safety, <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> said, `` It never stops being one.''
