<HEAD>Mao's Grandson a `Huge Monster' But an Average Student</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chairman <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s grandson might be tall and hefty but that's the only thing that makes him stand out in a crowd, a newspaper reported today. <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said the 18-year-old grandson of late leader <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> `` could be considered a ` huge monster' when compared with the average high school student.'' <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Xinyu </PERSON>, who stands 5-foot, 10-inches tall and weighs nearly 220 pounds, is the son of <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Anqing </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON>'s only known living son. A report last December said the 62-year-old <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Anqing </PERSON>, his wife, <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaohua </PERSON>, and their only son were living quietly in a <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> villa. <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> married four times and had nine children, including a daughter by his last wife, <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Qing </PERSON>. He died in 1976. <PERSON> Jiang </PERSON> <PERSON> Qing </PERSON> is believed alive. Detailed reports of the lives of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leaders and their families are rare. The paper described the high school senior as an amiable and cheerful youth who gets along well with his classmates and is treated just like any other student. He is fond of history `` perhaps because of the historical legacy of his forefathers,'' and his best grades are in history class, the report said. Besides his schoolbooks and some historical writings, <PERSON> Xinyu </PERSON> also likes to read classical novels, historical drama and classical poetry, it said. As he prepares for the nationwide college entrance exams that will be administered next month, <PERSON> Xinyu </PERSON> is still trying to decide what to study. He likes history, but thinks law or philosophy might be more practical, the newspaper said. Philosophy is considered practical in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> because graduates in the field are often assigned jobs in poweful propaganda bureaus. <PERSON> Xinyu </PERSON> was born Jan. 17, 1970, in the midst of the ultra-leftist Cultural Revolution, and rarely saw his father for the first six years of his life, the report said. `` However, this has not prevented <PERSON> Xinyu </PERSON> from respecting his father,'' the report said. <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Anqing </PERSON> is believed to suffer from mental illness, but the paper made no mention of his health. <PERSON> Xinyu </PERSON>'s classmates often discuss their impressions of Chairman <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> and his mistakes, and <PERSON> Xinyu </PERSON> willingly joins in these discussion, it said. `` Actually, except that he is <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>'s grandson, <PERSON> Xinyu </PERSON>'s appraisal of this great historical figure is no different from that of his classmates,'' the report said. Since the end of the Cultural Revolution in 1976, <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> has been criticized for creating a cult of personality and for leftist excesses that drove <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economy into the ground.
