<HEAD>Party Conference to Take Up Freer Economic Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Speakers at next week's national <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> conference will plea for greater economic competition in the state-run economy, an adviser to Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> Abalkin </PERSON>, head of the economics institute in the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, called Friday for an `` atmosphere of competition, winning over the consumer,'' and open competition by individual enterprises for state orders. Reformers have heavily criticized the centrally controlled system of economic planning. However, <PERSON> Abalkin </PERSON> said the country's economic system will be radically changed beginning in the early 1990s, and those changes will be discussed at the conference that begins Tuesday. <PERSON> Abalkin </PERSON> said several speeches to the conference of 5,000 delegates will be devoted to encouraging economic competition. His comments represented one of the few signs from officials of a specific topic to be considered and an indication of the issue's importance in the eyes of economic reformers The economist is a delegate to the party conference and a key adviser to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Several speeches to the party conference will criticize the system of government procurement, now accomplished by a vast system of orders to individual state-run businesses, he said. Reforms do n't intend to do away with government procurement, but change `` the ways they reach the enterprises, not the old ways _ command and bureaucratic _ but the method based on competition between enterprises to win government orders,'' <PERSON> Abalkin </PERSON> said. `` I am certain that more than one statement will be devoted to this question,'' he said. He added that satisfying pent-up demand for consumer goods and services `` will be possible only if the monopolization by the producer is ruled out and economic competition between individual enterprises is asserted.'' Reformers trace many of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s economic problems to a bureaucratic system of management that stifles local initiative and ignores market demands. Asked about a radical Estonian economic program for the party conference, <PERSON> Abalkin </PERSON> said central authorities must allow local officials more economic freedom but be careful not to permit a rise of nationalism. The Estonian platform for the party conference asks central authorities to give the republic complete control over prices, wages and investment policy. Officials have indicated that the conference will discuss problems among the more than 100 ethnic groups that live in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The problems have been highlighted in recent months by unrest in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> and other Baltic republics and a tense dispute between <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> over control of the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. The conference, the first since 1941, is to consider a program put forth by the party's policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that calls for party bureaucrats to stop interfering in government decisions and economic management. It also seeks to limit the terms of elected party officials.
