<HEAD>Official Report: Lebanon's Waters Not Radioactive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lebanese territorial waters are neither radioactive nor contaminated by tons of Italian toxic waste that have been dumped in recent months in this chaotic country, news reports said today. <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s daily <ORGANIZATION> As-Safir </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Lebanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> issued a report saying the waters were not contaminated after an expert committee examined samples of sea water Friday. A Lebanese businessman imported 2,400 tons of toxic chemical waste from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> two weeks ago and some of it was reported dumped on the <LOCATION> Kesrouan </LOCATION> coastal strip 20 miles north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. In addition, about 40 barrels inscribed `` <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> Oil'' and containing suspicious-looking pink and golden powder were discovered off the coast of Tyre in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Tabarja </LOCATION> in the north. The two events, combined with an outbreak of skin rashes among people who swam in the sea, drove the usually stoic Lebanese off their beaches. `` The contents of the barrels, the sea water and fish examined are not radioactive,'' said the report. `` The barrels contain organic brown powder that does not include any heavy poisonous metallic material,'' it said. The ministry qualifed the report in saying it was sending `` maritime biological and geological samples for further examination abroad to determine whether future risks are involved.'' It did not elaborate or say where it was sending the samples. The statement urged the Lebanese not to swim in the sea and to avoid eating fish, pending the outcome of the final report expected in two weeks.
