 Workers began to dismantle the exterior of a derailed <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> tanker in preparation for its move to a safe place today after awaiting the burnout of a toxic fire that prompted the evacuation of 15,000. The fire had died down enough by late Friday to allow workers to remove the ruptured steel jacket of the car. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> `` </PERSON> <PERSON> Mike </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Molloy </PERSON>, executive director of the state <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disaster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, said a survey team determined at mid-afternoon Friday that 20 percent of the caustic white phosphorus remained in the tanker. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, a DES spokesman, said plans called for placing the hull on a flat-bed rail car today and shipping it to a safe area to remove the remaining phosphorus. About 40 families displaced when the tanker derailed Wednesday night, creating a toxic cloud that forced the evacuation of 15,000 people from eight western <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> counties, will be allowed to return home once the car is removed, <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> conducted a drug test on the train's engineer, but the results will not be available for several weeks, said <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hensley </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hensley </PERSON> refused to identify the engineer. The tanker was part of a <ORGANIZATION> CSX </ORGANIZATION> train that officials say was going too fast through rural <LOCATION> Christian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> when 34 of its cars derailed Wednesday night in a rav