<HEAD>Congressional Committee Investigates Hunger In Appalachia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Poor mothers told a congressional committee investigating hunger in <LOCATION> Appalachia </LOCATION> that their families would not have enough food to live on if they did n't grow some of it themselves. Two congressmen, committee staff members and reporters visited homes of poor West Virginians on Friday before they listened to experts tell why some people go without food. `` The problems -LRB- with poverty programs -RRB- all originate with the notion that low-income people are deadbeats, lazy and shiftless people. This is not true,'' said <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Ogle </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Appalachian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> based in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>. Testifying before the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hunger </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Ogle </PERSON> said much of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s problem stems from the lack of money to supplement federal programs. That's because much of the state's wealth _ its surface land and mineral resources _ is controlled by out-of-state corporations. `` The absentee holders of wealth display an arrogance based on power that causes our state leaders to crumble and turn to mush,'' <PERSON> Ogle </PERSON> said. `` Thus, the burden of paying for public services falls disproportionately on low - and moderate-income people. The situation in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and other rural states appears to be dire, said Rep. <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. `` We have heard from mothers in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> that they would not be able to adequately feed their families if they did n't have their gardens,'' said <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>, the committee chairman. `` For many residents of this state, the outlook for prosperity in the near future is dismal. Most families do n't even think about how things look down the road because they are exhausting every thread of energy confronting the day-to-day struggles of making ends meet. But West Virginians are a proud people and they will stretch themselves to the farthest limits to survive.'' Earlier, the committee toured the homes of several residents to learn how they manage to make ends meet when state and federal programs are insufficient. <PERSON> Ocie </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, a 90-year-old resident of <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, told the congressmen she cherishes her independence but fears that it is threatened by her inability to make ends meet on Social Security, a modest <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> pension and the local Meals on Wheels program. `` When I get so I ca n't wait on myself, I hope the good Lord takes me,'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said. `` They want me to come live with my children, but I'd rather live in my own house.'' Down the road in <LOCATION> Robson </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gwendolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> is having an even harder time feeding herself and two children, her 3-year-old son and a 6-year-old girl she took in when the girl was abandoned by her mother. Because the little girl's mother is reluctant to allow her to be adopted, Cole _ who lives on $ 201 a month in welfare benefits and $ 228 a month in food stamps _ has been unable to obtain medical coverage for the child. `` What if she gets sick? I just pray that she do n't,'' <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. Often, <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>'s food stamps do n't stretch nearly far enough. With nearly a week remaining before she gets her next allotment of stamps, she showed visitors a refrigerator virtually empty of anything except some bread and bottles of water that she has because her water pipes are broken. `` I was working, but now that I've got the kids I ca n't,'' said the single mother. The nearest available day care center is in <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, 20 miles away, and <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> has no transportation of her own. `` Whatever job I could get, I'd have to take the bus, and getting the kids to day care would be hard,'' she said.
