<HEAD>Papal Message: Christians Also Suffered Under Nazis</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with today's comments. PICKS up
4th graf, `In addition ...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Pope, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> has been using his Austrian visit to emphasize that Christians as well as Jews were among the victims of Nazi persecution. Shortly after arriving in <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> on Thursday afternoon, the pontiff began drawing attention to the non-Jews who suffered under <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> dictator <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>. The pontiff did not mention Jews during his formal, televised speech during a Friday afternoon visit to the site of the former <ORGANIZATION> Mauthausen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> death camp, angering <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s chief rabbi by the omission. Today, the pontiff again brought up Christian suffering during a prayer service in the town of <LOCATION> Lorch </LOCATION>, 25 miles from the Czech border. `` Not far from here is <LOCATION> Mauthausen </LOCATION>, where Christians, Jews and others were persecuted for many reaons, including their religion, `` the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said. `` Their suffering was a gift to the world. `` In addition to killing six million Jews, the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> also killed hundred of thousand of others, including gypsies, homosexuals, priests and political opponents On his five-day Austrian tour, the pope appeared to be trying to make sure the memories of the other victims, especially Christians, are not forgotten. `` Amongst the many who were persecuted for religious, racial and political reasons were large numbers of Catholics _ priests, members of religious orders and lay people,'' he told President <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> and other Austrian politicians Thursday evening. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> also brought up the issue in a meeting with leaders of <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s Jewish community Friday morning as he talked about inquiries into the causes of the Nazi dictatorship. The pope spoke of studies into the `` the Holocaust as well as martyrdom of the Polish people and other European peoples during the Nazi era.'' Many of the Poles who were killed _ though not all _ were Jews. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> reminded the Jewish community leaders that the Nazi machine was aimed not only at the Jewish people `` but also against the faith of those who worship <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nazareth </LOCATION>, a Jew, as the savior of the world.'' Then, in an emotional visit to the site of the former death camp on Friday afternoon, the only victims he mentioned by name were Polish priest <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maximilian </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolbe </PERSON>, religious activist <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Callo </PERSON> and two other Catholics. He also called attention to `` all people, especially those who, when World War II was raging in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, suffered the torture of such camps.'' Austrian chief Rabbi <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON> responded to the <LOCATION> Mauthausen </LOCATION> speech by saying: `` A visit to <LOCATION> Mauthausen </LOCATION> without mentioning the word ` Jews' once is not satisfactory.'' `` The only Jew he mentions who suffered is <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>, and he did n't die in <LOCATION> Mauthausen </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON> added. The pontiff's pronouncements come as some historians have been promoting revised views of the Holocaust and <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> atrocities. Conservative West German historians in particular are saying that Nazi horrors should be compared with Stalinist-era mass killings in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and similar atrocities by totalitarian regimes. The historians' views have angered many Jews, who say they are denigrating the memory of Jews who died in the Holocaust. It is not known whether the pope is versed in this historical debate. However, after condemning the Nazi atrocities at <LOCATION> Mauthausen </LOCATION>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> used the phrase: `` Here ... and in so many places under totalitarian rule.'' Later in the speech, he added: `` If a machine of destruction still exists anywhere in the world, tell us, what can our century pass on to the generations to come?''
</TEXT>
