<HEAD>EPA: School Is First In Nation To Be Cited Under Asbestos Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Workers chipping away at old floor tiles in the hallway of a suburban high school sent clouds of dust containing cancer-causing asbestos into the air, federal officials charged. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> lodged a complaint and proposed a $ 5,000 fine against <ORGANIZATION> Thornton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Township </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Harvey </LOCATION>, a spokeswoman said Friday. It is the first complaint the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has brought under new asbestos-safety rules that went into effect in December. The complaint says students and other school personnel were exposed to asbestos fibers during the improper removal of 6,400 square feet of hallway flooring. `` We had received several calls from teachers and students and actually the workers in the school that the tile was being removed in the hallway and clouds of dust were being raised, and they were very concerned about it,'' said <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>. School officials have until July 11 to respond to the complaint, which names <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> High School District 205. The school was closed Friday afternoon, and officials could not be reached for comment. The violations were discovered during an <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> inspection March 1, and the school immediately discontinued the flooring removal project at the agency's request, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. Asbestos, a mineral that has been used in building materials, can cause lung cancer and other disorders when airborne fibers enter the body. When the tile was removed in February, school officials did not initially know that it contained asbestos, Ms. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. Later, officials had the tile tested and the presence of asbestos was confirmed, she said. Workers who were not accredited by the government to remove asbestos `` had sanded, chipped and cut the tiles, releasing clouds of dust containing asbestos,'' the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said in a news release. The complaint against <PERSON> Thornton </PERSON> is the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s first enforcement action nationwide under the Asbestos Hazard Emergency Response Act, the agency said. Under the law, which took effect Dec. 14, specific safety measures must be taken when removing asbestos from elementary and secondary schools. If they decide to contest the complaint, school officials can seek an informal hearing with <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> or request a hearing before a federal administrative law judge, Ms. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said.
