ement from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Also faulting the pontiff on Friday was <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s chief rabbi <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenberg </PERSON>, who leads the country's 12,000 Jews. On Friday while at <LOCATION> Mauthausen </LOCATION>, the pontiff cited only four concentration camp victims by name, all of them Catholics. However, he stopped in silence for nearly a minute at a plaque set up in memory of the Jewish victims. <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON> said the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>, standing beside a camp survivor in front of the plaque, spoke of the Jews and said `` never again'' three times. <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON> said the survivor was supposed to have been wearing a tiny microphone so that the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s words could have been heard but that for some reason officials had removed the device.
