 Almost one-third of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s labor force may lose their jobs as a result of the government's economic austerity program, a trade union leader was quoted as saying <PERSON> Dusan </PERSON> <PERSON> Koceljevic </PERSON> made the statement during a session of a government commission which is preparing economic reforms, the <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Politika </ORGANIZATION> reported. The government earlier this month began an economic austerity program to ease <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s 170 percent inflation rate and its $ 21 billion foreign and to steer the country toward a more open market. The government also linked wages and employment to the currently low industrial productivity. As a result, wage cuts of up to 30 percent have been enforced under the new measure. `` Because of the restructuring of the economy, 2 million workers will lose their jobs,'' <PERSON> Koceljevic </PERSON> was quoted as saying. About 1.1 million Yugoslavs are unemployed, out of a labor force of 6.6 million.
