<HEAD>Report: British Hostages To Be Freed Before U.S. Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> magazine reported today that the Iranian government hopes to influence the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential elections by releasing British hostages close to the Nov. 8 vote. The weekly Ash-Shiraa reported that the agreement to release the hostages emerged during a three-day unofficial visit by four British legislators to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> that ended Wednesday. `` Reliable Moslem fundamentalist circles have confirmed that British-Iranian negotiations to free British hostages held in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> will result -LRB- in their release -RRB- on the eve of the American presidential elections,'' the report said. The magazine gained international fame when it broke the story of secret <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms sales to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in return for releasing American hostages in 1986. The magazine's more recent reports on hostage developments have proved inaccurate. The four British legislators returned to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Wednesday saying <LOCATION> Iranian </LOCATION> officials offered to use their influence to release the three British captives in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ash-Shiraa </PERSON> said the `` Iranian leadersip was seeking to postpone the release until late summer so that it will be the biggest voter in the coming <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidential elections.'' <PERSON> Ash-Shiraa </PERSON> said the Iranian move of postponing the release `` aims at besieging and embarrassing the official <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> stand -LRB- of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration -RRB-'' for failing to obtain the release of American hostages. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> had agreed not to negotiate for the hostages' release. However, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> `` negotiated with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> for the release of French hostages and that was achieved'' the report said. French diplomats <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Fontaine </PERSON> and <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Carton </PERSON> as well as journalist <PERSON> Jean-Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kauffmann </PERSON> were released in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> May 4. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s foreign secretary, Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>, on Thursday denied that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> was negotiating for the release of <ORGANIZATION> Anglican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> envoy <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Waite </PERSON>, journalist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> and teacher <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Keenan </PERSON>. No group has claimed responsibility for abducting <PERSON> Waite </PERSON> and <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, although they are widely believed held by fanatic Shiite Moslem kidnappers affiliated with the Iranian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God. The magazine report compared the anticipated release to that of of 52 Americans held hostage in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> for 444 days. They were released on inauguration day as president <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> left office. `` The aim of the delay was to bring <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> down and the hostages were only released after a new president -LRB- President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> -RRB- took over'' the magazine article concluded. In all, 18 foreigners are missing and believed kidnapped in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, including nine Americans. The longest held is <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
