<HEAD>Mrs. Thatcher's Characteristic Candor Causes Uproar in Canada</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A cartoon in the <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> Star captured the scene: with dynamite bulging out of her purse, a smiling <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> marches away from the Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> as an explosion blows the top off the building. Such was the impact of the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> prime minister's characteristically forthright expression of conservative views last week in a speech to a joint session of Parliament Not since French President <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON> intervened in the <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> separatist debate in 1967 by declaring `` Vive le Quebec Libre!'' -LRB- Long live a free <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> -RRB- has a foreign leader stirred so much controversy. Fresh from the <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Summit </ORGANIZATION>, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Ottawa </LOCATION> for talks with Conservative Prime Minister <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> and to accept an invitation to address Parliament. A standing ovation greeted her, but Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> quickly angered opposition parties by endorsing <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON>'s Free Trade Agreement with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and his decision to buy a $ 6.6 billion fleet of nuclear-powered submarines. Both the main opposition <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the socialist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> were outraged, and a furious exchange erupted two hours later during Commons question period. `` What right does she have to come here and meddle in <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> affairs?'' <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Broadbent </PERSON> shouted. Liberal leader <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> asked if <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> had vetted <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s remarks, they were so partisan. `` We are no longer a colony of <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and we do not want to become a colony of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said. Both opposition parties say they will tear up the trade deal and cancel the submarine program if they win the next election, which <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> may call as early as this fall. The New Democrats also want to take <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> out of the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> paid special tribute to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s contribution to the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, including its decision to permit tests of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cruise missiles and bolster its navy with nuclear-powered subs. She also took a broad swipe at the `` the debilitating concept of the all-powerful state'' before embracing the Canada-U.S. Free Trade Agreement, which would dismantle trade barriers over a 10-year period. The Liberals and New Democrats say the deal sacrifices independence and threatens to make <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> the 51st state of the union. `` On the basis of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s experience of joining the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, you need have no fear that <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s national personality will be in any way diminished,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said. `` Fifteen years of <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> membership have left our people no less British and no less proud of their history and independence. Moreover, protectionism is not a life belt which keeps an economy afloat; it is a millstone that drags you down and penalizes consumers and work force alike.'' Liberal <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Axworthy </PERSON> likened Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s intervention to a <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> prime minister telling the British what to do about <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. In defense of Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazankowski </PERSON> called the opposition `` whiners and complainers.'' Ironically, there were no protests a week earlier when West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> addressed the same chamber and, in a more general way, endorsed both the Free Trade Agreement and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s contribution to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>. Sensitivities were much greater toward Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, since it was only in 1981 that <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> repatriated its Constitution from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and since Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> remains <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s head of state. The opposition suggested that Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> may have been trying to butter up <PERSON> Mulroney </PERSON> in hopes he will opt for the British Trafalgar-class submarine over its French rival, the Rubis-Amethyst. By week's end, furor over the speech had turned to humor. <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> columnist <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautens </PERSON> offered Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> some advice on a few problems of her own. He suggested a two-year sabbatical for composer <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Webber </PERSON>, of `` Phantom of the Opera'' and `` Cats'' fame, `` so somebody else can have a chance to write a musical.'' <PERSON> Lautens </PERSON> also asked Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> to ban the use of incomprehensible British expressions such as `` lift'' -LRB- elevator -RRB-, `` tube'' -LRB- subway train -RRB- and `` bonnet'' -LRB- car hood -RRB-. `` While I'm at it,'' <PERSON> Lautens </PERSON> added, `` send some Brits to this country immediately so we can teach them how to make a good hamburg, not one of those Wimpy things.''
