<HEAD>Rescuers Resume Search With Little Hope of Finding Survivors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, ``Three West ...'' to UPDATE number of
missing; picks up 9th graf pvs: Trabzon gov....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VEDAT ERDAMAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CATAK, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rescue workers aided by search dogs fanned out over this rain-soaked village today, trying to unearth about 100 people buried by a landslide. Officials said there was little chance of finding survivors. `` I am nearly sure that no one will come out alive,'' said <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> <PERSON> Krctschemer </PERSON>, head of a 32-member West German volunteer team from the <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dog </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's very little space for air pockets here, between the soft earth and the rocks, where someone trapped could breathe. But we have to go on looking,'' added <PERSON> Klaus </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolter </PERSON>, another member of the German team. Rescue efforts resumed at sunrise today. The search had been called off during the night after geologists and engineers spotted cracks in the mountain that could trigger another devastating slide. <PERSON> Krctschemer </PERSON> said the rescue workers had located the spot where the landslide had buried a coffeehouse crowded with breakfast-time customers on Thursday. He said they were trying to reach the coffeehouse by digging holes from two sides. He said rescuers should be able to unearth some bodies from the site later in the day. Villagers said about 30 travelers were in the restaurant at the time of the disaster and dozens more were at the roadside waiting for bulldozers to clear the highway after an earlier rockfall. Three West German tourists and 41 Turks were listed as missing. There were also unconfirmed reports by witnesses that two British tourists had been in the coffeehouse, but it could not be determined whether they had been buried in the landslide or had left before the disaster. <LOCATION> Trabzon </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Enver </PERSON> <PERSON> Hizlan </PERSON> said there probably would be delay in listing other names because the people involved were in transit. Rescue efforts were hindered by new slides that swept clouds of dust into the air and sent giant boulders hurtling down the wooded mountainside. A Turkish truck driver and a villager were injured in separate rockfalls on Friday. Another landslide hit an area about three miles away from <LOCATION> Catak </LOCATION> today, closing the main highway. No injuries were reported. Grieving relatives watched the rescue works, occasionally kneeling over a hole and looking down with empty eyes. `` Do you think anyone can come out alive from there?'' asked <PERSON> Necati </PERSON> <PERSON> Himtas </PERSON>, whose 20-year-old son was missing. A woman wailing and weeping was taken to the mobile hospital when she fainted. Catak, home to 1,000 people, is situated 19 miles from the <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Trabzon </LOCATION> on a main highway leading to eastern Anatolia and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The two-lane highway was widened three years ago to handle increasing truck and tourist traffic, but vilagers said it was not buttressed properly. `` The retaining walls were n't big enough and we started having landslides, not big ones but enough to block the road,'' said <PERSON> Riza </PERSON> <PERSON> Yavuz </PERSON>, the village headman. <PERSON> Yavuz </PERSON> said the coffeehouse owner had told public works officials earlier this month that the hillside needed more support or it would collapse. <PERSON> Erkan </PERSON> <PERSON> Omarbeyoglou </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s director of highways, warned that new cracks had appeared on the same stretch of mountainside, suggesting another section could be dislodged. `` There's a risk that an entire hilltop could come crashing down in the same area,'' <PERSON> Omarbeyoglou </PERSON> said. He said rescue workers would have enough warning to evacuate the area. The landslide Thursday also destroyed a restaurant, 20 homes and a high school closed for summer vacation. A stream burst its banks and flooded another part of the village, including several houses. `` I saw a telegraph pole slowly bending over,'' said <PERSON> Gaby </PERSON> <PERSON> Engler </PERSON>, a 28-year-old West German nurse, who witnessed the slide. `` I heard a noise like an explosion and the whole hillside came away in front of me.''
