<HEAD>With AM-Bakke Anniversary Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the decade since a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision in the <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakke </PERSON> case ended the use of enrollment quotas, the number of minority students admitted to medical school actually increased in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colleges </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Petersdorf </PERSON>, president of the association, said that in 1978 it was feared that the Bakke decision, which forbids the use of special consideration in the admission of minorities, would cause medical schools to enroll even fewer minorities than before. `` The opposite proved to be true,'' <PERSON> Petersdorf </PERSON> said. In the first enrollment period after the Bakke decision, 40.9 percent of the minority students who applied to medical schools were admitted, and minority enrollees composed 8.7 percent of first-year medical school classes. Ten years later, <PERSON> Petersdorf </PERSON> said, the medical schools are admitting 51.7 percent of the minority applicants and they now represent 10.2 percent of the entering classes. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision actually encouraged affirmative action goals by allowing the use of race and other determinants in addition to academic achievement as acceptable admissions criteria,'' <PERSON> Petersdorf </PERSON> said. He said that medical schools began affirmative action steps in 1970 and the <PERSON> Bakke </PERSON> decision `` reaffirmed'' them.
