<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal regulators give <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> money centers with troubled overseas loans more leeway than <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> banks hobbled by declines in oil prices and a deflated real estate market, Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said Saturday. `` The result is that domestic borrowers have greater difficulty acquiring credit than borrowers like <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said in a letter urging the chiefs of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and the comptroller of the currency to review their regulatory practices. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said recent data indicate banks must set aside greater reserves against domestic troubled loans than against troubled loans to Third World and Eastern Bloc nations. `` This favorable treatment by regulators of troubled foreign loans over domestic loans will crimp credit to domestic borrowers,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> wrote <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON>, comptroller of the currency. `` This is particularly important to areas like <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> whose banks hold a disproportionate share of troubled domestic loans,'' wrote <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>. As the state attempts to rebuild its economy, it needs a `` robust and healthy banking system able to provide needed credit to worthy borrowers ranking from small businesses to ranchers and farmers.'' <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> Seidman </PERSON> had not seen the letter and could not comment on it. But he said regulators were not being any more stringent on <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> banks than those elsewhere in the country. Rates for reserves set aside for foreign loans depend on a variety of factors, including the country, the loan and the bank, <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Cross </PERSON>, an aide to <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON>, said the comptroller shared <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s concerns about the problems in the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> economy and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> banks, but he wanted to see the figures on which the senator's letter was based before commenting further. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> data indicate that an amount comparable to 51 percent of non-performing domestic loans is being held as loan loss reserves. But calculations by the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> suggest that `` considerably smaller reserves _ only 24 percent _ are being set aside against troubled loans by banks to Third World and Eastern Bloc nations,'' he wrote. `` I think this is unfair and unequal treatment,'' said <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>. `` I would much rather have a loan collateralized by an empty building in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> than to depend on the commitments of a foreign communist country like <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said he was drafting legislation to correct `` that kind of slanted treatment, favoring the big money banks in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> banks.'' `` It really hurts not just the banks in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, but the borrowers too, because we do n't have sufficient capital _ that means for small businesses, medium-sized businesses,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said.
