<FIRST>r i AM-CentralBank     06-25 0782</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central Bank,0803</SECOND>
<HEAD>Support Growing For European `Federal Reserve' Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Creation of a West European central bank, an idea that gained little currency in the past, is quietly emerging as a long-range priority of the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. The prospect of establishing a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Federal Reserve-style central bank for <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> is expected to be a major topic of discussion at an <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> summit conference starting June 27 in <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. But decisions to take the first concrete steps toward a `` Eurobank'' to manage a common monetary policy are not likely in <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION>, analysts say. Many other related questions, such as harmonizing tax policies in the Common Market, probably will have to be settled first. <PERSON> Norbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>, senior economist at <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, says establishment of a central bank for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> probably is still `` a long way off.'' Some <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> members, such as <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, do n't like the idea. They think it would force them to surrender too much national control. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> has not even heeded her <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> partners' urgings to include <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in the European Monetary System, which was created in 1979 to keep European currency values stable. Yet talk of a European currency union is becoming more serious than just a year ago, when the idea _ which has been discussed off and on for more than two decades _ was generally dismissed as a pipe dream. `` It is not just utopia, it is not nirvana. It is something that can be accepted in the <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> of today,'' <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. Many European leaders have come to believe that the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s plan for creating a true common market by 1992 _ one that allows goods, people and money to freely cross national borders _ increases the need for a European central bank to cope with less rigid capital markets. This feeling has been reinforced by a June 13 agreement by European finance ministers to remove national controls on capital movements by July 1990 in the eight most advanced <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> countries. The agreement excludes the four countries that have joined the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> since 1973 _ <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> were given a deadline of 1992; <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> have until 1995. <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON>, the West German finance minister, hailed the accord as `` a milestone of great importance'' on the path to unifying the European market and increasing the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s global competitiveness. At the <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION> summit, West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> is expected to propose that a special panel of central bank officials and other experts from <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> countries be set up to study the central bank issue. `` This is a topic that is clearly gaining pace,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>, senior <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> economist at the London-based investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Drew </PERSON>. The eventual structure of a European central bank is far from clear, but one idea is to model it after the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, with regional representatives and independently appointed governors. <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> is a strong supporter of establishing a true European monetary union, with a central bank as the linchpin, but the independent <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>, or German central bank, has been cool to the idea. `` The vision of a <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> union is most certainly closely bound with that of a European currency union,'' <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> told a recent <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> conference. Even though one of the original aims of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> was to create an economic and monetary union, all the member nations still have their own currencies and set their own policies on interest rates and money supply. An embryonic regional currency, known as the European currency unit, or Ecu, has been in use since 1979, but mainly as an accounting device. The Ecu does not exist as a hard currency in bank notes or coins, except for a special issue of Ecu coins last year by <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> to commemorate the 30th anniversary of the founding of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>. The Ecu is based on an average of Common Market currencies and currently is worth about $ 1.20. A European central bank would, in the vision held by many supporters of an <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> monetary union, be the manager of the Ecu _ much as the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> manages the dollar _ by influencing interest rate levels and controlling the supply of money in the economy. One of the main questions to be settled is whether a European monetary authority could co-exist with national central banks or whether it would replace them. If this and other complex issues are resolved, European economic integration will have advanced much further than even the most ardent European unionists would have believed possible in the early 1980s.
</TEXT>
