<HEAD>Guild Walkout Affecting Everyone From Studio Moguls to Dry
Cleaners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With no end in sight to the 4-month-old writers strike, thousands of workers who depend on movie and TV production for a living face a summer of dwindling savings accounts and mounting bills. From Sunset Strip restaurants to dry cleaners in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fernando </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> community and the businesses that profit from it are withering on the vine at a time when activity should be at its peak in preparation for the fall harvest of new television shows and Oscar-contending movies. `` I hope this strike ends soon,'' said <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> of the family-owned La Boutique Dry Cleaners in suburban <LOCATION> Sherman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oaks </LOCATION>, home to many film and TV performers and workers. `` They were coming in with their silk shirts and wool gabardine suits. Now they come in with their T-shirts and <PERSON> Levis </PERSON>.'' Members of the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> voted Wednesday to continue their walkout, rejecting by a 3-to-1 margin a `` final offer'' from the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION>. The writers went on strike March 7 over the issues of payments for reruns of one-hour shows and programs broadcast in foreign markets, as well as creative control. Virtually all programming for the fall season has been idled. The exceptions are some independently produced shows that have signed their own guild contracts, including `` The Cosby Show'' and `` The Tonight Show.'' In addition, work on the studios' major theatrical movies for the fall and winter seasons _ traditionally a time when many potential Academy Award nominees are released _ has been curtailed. `` It's devastating,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Slusser </PERSON>, senior vice president and general manager of <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION>. `` We've already made a number of cutbacks in the TV and studio operations group.'' Even the famous Universal commissary is affected. On Friday it was closed and its employees laid off until further notice. `` This city is designed for the entertainment industry, and this is destroying it,'' said <PERSON> Newt </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellis </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Unitel </ORGANIZATION>, a major post-production facility on the lot of <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bellis </PERSON> said his business, which handles editing and sound-dubbing for TV shows such as `` Family Ties,'' has been down 50 percent since the strike. He has not laid off any of his 60 employees `` because I have not had the heart to do it,'' he said. `` But my feeling is that if this goes on, I'm going to have to cut my staff at least 60 percent. But I wo n't as long as I can hold out and my bank will stay with me.'' Many of those affected by the strike are studio workers represented by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theatrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>, and Local 44 President <PERSON> Mac </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> said his members are looking at dwindling bank accounts. `` I've had several calls looking for help in mortgages and car payments,'' <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> said. `` These people do n't work 52 weeks a year normally. Now they're not working on the weeks they normally have.'' His union local, with 3,750 members, was 60 percent unemployed, compared with 28 percent for the same time last year. The union includes special effects technicians, decorators, prop makers, upholsterers and drapers. At Art's Deli in <LOCATION> Studio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, owner <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Ginsburg </PERSON> estimated business was down 10 percent to 15 percent at one of the area's favorite gathering spots for show business dealmaking `` Not only are we missing the writers and producers, but the agents meeting with their clients, the studio drivers and all the people in the industry,'' <PERSON> Ginsburg </PERSON> said. `` It's a related thing all down the line.'' Recently at the historic <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> haunt <PERSON> Musso </PERSON> and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>'s, two of the town's most important men sat unrecognized for hours at one of the tables: Producers Alliance President <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Counter </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> chief negotiator <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Walton </PERSON>. The informal session failed to settle the dispute, but they were never interrupted as they bargained inside the venerable show business restaurant that their differences had helped to empty.
