<FIRST>r a AM-ContraSuit     06-25 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contra Suit,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Stops Intriguing, Expensive Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge's decision to throw out a $ 24 million lawsuit that mixed the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, Contras and the <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cocaine cartel has left lingering questions, charges of politics, big bills and little doubt that litigation will continue. Chief U.S. District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> ruled Thursday that the two journalists who filed the suit failed to prove their allegations that the 29 defendants conspired in a guns-for-drugs scheme or a 1984 terrorist bombing in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The defendants included Iran-Contra figures <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Secord </PERSON> and <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>, <PERSON> Contra </PERSON> leader <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>, former <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> deputy director of operations <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Shackley </PERSON>, and retired major general and anti-communist crusader <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Singlaub </PERSON>. The suit was filed in May 1986, six months before the Iran-Contra affair became public. Many of the people it brought to light, such as <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hakim </PERSON>, <PERSON> Calero </PERSON> and <PERSON> Singlaub </PERSON>, have been indicted or forced to appear before congressional committees investigating that case. The suit involved heroin smuggling from <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>, the `` Phoenix'' assassination program in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, the Bay of Pigs fiasco, cocaine smuggling from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, illegal <LOCATION> Contra </LOCATION> arms running, bombings, threats, disappearances _ all to push what the plaintiffs believed was a rabid right-wing ideology. On the side of the journalists, <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Avirgan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Honey </PERSON>, was the liberal, Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> Christic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> and their attorney, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON>, a veteran of suits on behalf of radiation victim <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Silkwood </PERSON> and against the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION>. Both sides say politics was at the root of the case, which was to go to trial Monday. `` I think it was 100 percent political,'' says <PERSON> Singlaub </PERSON>. `` I think their real agenda is to discredit the intelligence service, discredit the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration in general and to discredit <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.'' The vice president led the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> at the time <PERSON> Shackley </PERSON> was allegedly involved in the conspiracy, and later while vice president, the <PERSON> Christics </PERSON> said, his office was aware of arms smuggling to the Contras. The <ORGANIZATION> Christic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> explanation is a mirror image of <PERSON> Singlaub </PERSON>'s. They say the politics involved was not theirs, but rather that of the judge who favored the defendants and people in the government who pressured him to protect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` I believe what has happened here is that this ruling is not a legal ruling, it's a political ruling,'' said <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, director of the institute. `` The judge did n't want a political drama in his courtroom before the election.'' Both sides agree more litigation is in the wings. `` I have under active consideration plans to sue <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> for libel,'' said <PERSON> Secord </PERSON>. `` This suit ... has been from the beginning preposterous. Everyone thinks it's absurd and defaming and malicious.'' <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> is taking <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s decision to an appeals court but says he would be delighted to be the center of a libel trial. `` We'd be right back in court with all our witnesses and all our documents,'' he said. One reason the defendants are threatening countersuits is to recover the ruinously expensive costs of attending hearings, responding to voluminous motions, reading thousands of documents and taking depositions from hundreds of witnesses. The witness list submitted for the trial had more than 2,000 names. <PERSON> Singlaub </PERSON> said he spent more than $ 250,000 on his own defense, and his attorney, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON>, said the defendants collectively spent $ 1 million. It cost the <ORGANIZATION> Christic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> even more, $ 3 million, according Ms. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>. According to the suit, <PERSON> Shackley </PERSON> and others, using drug profits, assassinated officials first in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, then <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and other nations. The key event in the suit was the May 1984 bombing of a news conference held by <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> commander <PERSON> Eden </PERSON> <PERSON> Pastora </PERSON> in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penca </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. Three journalists and five <PERSON> Pastora </PERSON> supporters died in the explosion. <PERSON> Avirgan </PERSON> was hurt and his camera damaged in the explosion, allowing him to file a civil damage suit under federal law. The suit charged the bombing was arranged by <PERSON> Shackley </PERSON>, <PERSON> Contra </PERSON> leaders and others angered that <PERSON> Pastora </PERSON> refused to join anti-Sandinista groups he considered too close to the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> and deposed Nicaraguan dictator <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> <PERSON> Debayle </PERSON>.
