<FIRST>r w AM-WhiteHouse-Economy     06-25 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-White House-Economy,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sprinkel Predicts Clear Economic Sailing</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: RETRANSMITS a0593 to correct cycle designator</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's top economist predicts robust growth and low inflation will enhance <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign for the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, but some private analysts say the outlook is n't all that rosy Conventional wisdom says most people vote their pocketbooks. And according to <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON>, chairman of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>, `` Prospects for continued prosperity have seldom been better.'' The administration is looking for the sixth straight year of economic expansion, coupled with low inflation, to bolster Republican chances at the polls this November. <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON>, who was criticized as too optimistic late last year when he predicted strong, steady growth for 1988, issued new projections in the past week that look even better. He boosted his prediction of overall economic growth as measured by the gross national product from 2.9 percent _ the same as 1986 and 1987 _ to 3.5 percent. He cut his unemployment rate forecast from 5.8 percent to 5.5 percent and stuck to his estimate of consumer price inflation, 4.3 percent, the same as last year. `` This expansion, already in its precedent-breaking 67th month, now gives every indication of continuing at least through the end of this administration and on into next year,'' he said. Private economists, who six months ago accused <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON> of looking at the world through rose-colored glasses, now concede that his growth projections then were, if anything, too conservative. The lasting shock to consumer buying that economists thought would come from the October stock market crash never really materialized and some say even the administration's new and higher growth estimate is on target, even as they are more concerned about the inflation outlook. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s latest report on <ORGANIZATION> GNP </ORGANIZATION> said booming exports and a sharp increase in modernization and expansion spending by businesses pushed growth to 3.6 percent in the first quarter of this year after even stronger growth of 4.8 percent in the last quarter of 1987. Private analysts, however, part company with <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON>'s prediction that inflation will hold steady at about the same level as last year <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, head of an economic consulting firm in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, called the inflation numbers: `` Pie in the sky stuff.'' <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Straszheim </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION>, said the economy has `` really done better than anybody has a right to expect'' in making the transition from consumer-led to export-driven growth. But, he said the administration ca n't ignore the inflationary effect of the drought scorching the nation's midsection. Coming increases in the price of food, which accounts for one-fifth of all consumer purchases, likely will boost inflation to at least 5 percent, he said. <PERSON> Sprinkel </PERSON> agreed the severity of the rise in food prices remains uncertain, but said he has allowed for temporary increases. He said that packaging and distribution account for far more of the retail price of food than crop prices, and argued food prices were unlikely to add significantly to the underlying inflation rate because food represents only about 2 percent of GNP. However, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> Aubrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a government securities dealer, said a stiff jolt to food prices runs the risk of triggering `` inflation psychology'' that spills over into other sectors of the economy, just as the run up in oil prices did in the 1970s. `` The shading of the administration's estimates on inflation may involve at least some election-year politics in addition to economic analysis,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. `` What the administration is trying to do is present a picture of strong economic growth and low inflation as we come into an election.''
