<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is the text of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s weekly radio address, as delivered Saturday by Rep. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>: This is Congresswoman <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Boxer </PERSON> from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> I'd like to talk to you about the Pentagon scandal, and why <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is deeply troubled by it. You've heard about scandals before. But this one is different. It strikes at the heart of our national security, and, I believe, was fueled by a consistent message by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration that government is our enemy and big defense business our friend. If the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> is right, then secret information worth tens of billions has been traded by military insiders and defense contractors to line their pockets and undermine the competitive system that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has mandated. Why has this happened? I do n't agree with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> that it's `` understandable.'' Do you? Or with <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> who says there's nothing wrong with the system, it's just a few individuals. Where is the outrage? Where is the concern? The root cause of this scandal was alluded to more than 20 years ago by a president from the military, <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>. He warned about the unwarranted influence of the military-industrial complex, and the need for `` an alert citizenry'' to protect against it. I want you to be an alert citizenry. I want you to know what has gone on since this administration came to power in 1980. First, the military budget increased 100 percent from $ 150 billion to $ 300 billion today. Money was literally stuffed into the Pentagon with too little attention paid to cost or quality _ as if money alone could buy us security. We need a strong defense, but we must control wasteful spending. I want you to know that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has passed reforms. Each time we were told by the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> to butt out. But we said it was the people's business. In 1984 we showed them the $ 7,000 coffee pot and asked for reform. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said that was an isolated incident. So we showed them the $ 600 toilet seat, the $ 300 no-smoking sign, the $ 9,000 <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> wrench. All isolated incidents, they said. But we passed legislation to force competition on the $ 18 billion spare parts budget. But we knew there was more _ lots more. We said the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> and defense contractors were too cozy. The Pentagon said no. But we passed revolving door legislation, stopping military procurement officers from retiring and going to to work on Friday for the very same contractors they investigated on Thursday. Over Pentagon objections, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed strong whistleblower protection for those brave people who speak out about fraud and waste. This whole scandal unfolded because a whistleblower had the guts to speak out. In 1986, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> mandated a procurement czar to straighten out the mess. An honorable man took the job but quit, frustrated that he was fighting _ and losing _ every time. We legislated some good old-fashioned competition, and we said enough to buying from monopolies. But the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, the contractors, and the administration did n't like it They howled. They were unabashed in their contempt toward congressional reforms. They continued to try to water them down, repeal them or ignore them. Now, in this tterrible scandal there has apparently been the ultimate contempt _ as many as 50 consultants buying secret information to destroy competition and cheat all of us. It is difficult to see six years of bipartisan work foiled by what one news magazine calls `` a conspiracy of greed.'' But we will learn from this and you, alert citizens, can help. Let us send a message through our votes that we've had enough of pouring billions into a bottomless money pit. Let us send a message through our votes that we want an ethical and honorable independent procurement system. You know, the code name for this <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> investigation is `` Ill Wind.'' Let's turn this ill wind into winds of change _ for all of us. It's about time, do n't you think?
</TEXT>
