<HEAD>Soviets Says Their Warning on Afghan Pullout Meant As Pressure
Tactic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Foreign Ministry official indicated Saturday that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> never intended to halt its troop withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, as it threatened, and was only trying to put pressure on Afghan rebel supporters. The comments by Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Yuli </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON> seemed designed to put to rest speculation that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> might slow or stop withdrawing its troops from <LOCATION> Afghanstan </LOCATION> because of alleged violations of the accord providing for the withdrawal. He indicated the warnings were directed more at putting pressure on <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which supports the rebels, than signaling any Soviet backtracking. `` We are appealing to the conscience of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s leaders,'' <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON> said at a news conference, speaking through an interpreter. `` We believe that the leaders of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> will realize their responsibility and that the world's public will help them take awareness of their responsibilty.'' <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON>, who helped negotiate the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords, also called on reporters to investigate alleged Pakistani violations of the accord, signed April 14. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has been complaining almost daily that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s arms shipments to guerrillas fighting <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s government and that the location of rebel training bases in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> violate the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON> cited specific examples of alleged <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistani </LOCATION> support for the rebels. He said a Pakistani general, <PERSON> Sarfaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON>, is in charge of a camp near the village of <LOCATION> Kalan </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>, where 2,500 rebels are training. American advisers are also at the camp, <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON> said. The first Soviet warning of retaliation came May 28, when the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said that if <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> did not halt `` interference in the internal affairs of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>,'' the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> would `` draw pertinent conclusions with respect to the timetable of the troop withdrawal and take concrete steps.'' Under the accords, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> began pulling out its more than 100,000 troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on May 15 and is supposed to have half of them out by Aug. 15. The pullout is to be completed by Feb. 15. Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and Afghan President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> warned after a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> meeting on June 13 that Pakistani violations of the accord would bring `` resolute retaliatory steps.'' <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuznetsov </PERSON>, deputy head of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> desk in the Soviet Foreign Ministry, said in an interview the next day that the warning meant the withdrawing Soviet troops would strike back at <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> guerrillas who attack them. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been supplying the Afghan rebels with an estimated $ 500 million annually in arms and military supplies channeled through <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. It has vowed to continue the supplies as long as the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> keeps up its military support of the Afghan government. The <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accords prohibit Pakistani interference in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s affairs. But weapons supply from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is not banned. A separate agreement signed by <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> allows them to continue supplying their respective allies. Soviet troops intervened in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 following a communist coup there the previous year.
