<HEAD>Protesters Disrupt Performance of Controversial Play `The Deputy'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Protesters disrupted a performance of a play critical of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s role in dealing with the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> and said the production was improper during the papal visit to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. `` This whole play is a just a lie!'' about 50 protesters shouted late Friday during a performance of German author <PERSON> Rolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hochhuth </PERSON>'s play, `` The Deputy. Police took two protesters into custody. The incident occurred on the second day of Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hochhuth </PERSON>'s play, first performed in 1963 in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, alleges that then-Pope <PERSON> Pius </PERSON> <PERSON> XII </PERSON> failed to do enough to prevent the Nazi Holocaust. `` If I were writing the play again today, I would not present the personage of Pope <PERSON> Pius </PERSON> <PERSON> XII </PERSON> so favorably,'' <PERSON> Hochhuth </PERSON> said later during an informal discussion with the audience. The play already is very critical of <PERSON> Pius </PERSON> <PERSON> XII </PERSON>. The play's assistant director, <PERSON> Hermann </PERSON> <PERSON> Beil </PERSON>, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview that the demonstrators, predominantly young people, shouted and used whistles to attract attention during the performance at <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'s Burgtheater. <PERSON> Beil </PERSON> said some in the audience shouted back at the protesters: `` Out with the Nazis!'' The actors occasionally stopped to ask for silence. About 350 people were in the audience during the disruptions, <PERSON> Beil </PERSON> said. The protesters called themselves `` The Young Friends of the Burgtheater'' and distributed leaflets calling for the ouster of theater director <PERSON> Claus </PERSON> <PERSON> Peymann </PERSON>. `` Out with Peymann,'' some chanted. Peymann himself told the audience later, `` I think it ` s great that a public forum can arise in this theater. Perhaps the theater today has the function of presenting those questions that politics no longer deal with.'' Although critics reacted coolly to the play, it became a hit and sparked impassioned debate over the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>'s role before and during World War II. In addition to <PERSON> Hochhuth </PERSON>, many Jewish leaders allege the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> failed to do enough to prevent the mass murder of European Jews. But the current pope has strongly defended the church's role during the Nazi era. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> even brought up the subject on the current trip. `` The incomprehensible pain, suffering and tears still are before my eyes and etched deep in my soul,'' the pontiff said Friday in reference to the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> murder of 6 million Jews. But he continued: `` It would be clearly unjust and untrue to charge Christianity with these unspeakable crimes.'' The theater's production of the play sparked controversy last March, when it was performed at the time the Austrians were marking the 50th anniversary of the country's annexation by <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>.
