<FIRST>u p AM-Democrats-Rules 1stLd-Writethru a0607 06-25 0942</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Democrats-Rules, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0607,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Jackson Agree On Rules Overhaul, Avoiding Convention
Fight</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 15th graf pvs: The committee ... with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with committee approving change, quotes. Picks up 16th graf pvs
bgng: Devine said ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> agreed Saturday to an overhaul of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> rules and avoided the possibility of a contentious floor fight at next month's national convention. Under the agreement, the number of `` super delegates'' to the 1992 convention will be cut nearly in half and all other delegates would be awarded to presidential candidates in proportion to public support. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, meeting Saturday with local campaign officials in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, said the agreement represented `` a victory for the people ... a victory for democracy.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> had complained that party rules did not allow him to get the delegates he said were warranted by his popular support. He had said that he would carry his fight to the convention floor to get the rules changed. `` I think that we've made a lot of steps forward in a lot of areas that Rev. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has been concerned about,'' said <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Ickes </PERSON>, who negotiated for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> on the rules changes. Of the 643 super delegates to the convention, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who won 29 percent of the vote in the primaries, had just 55. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who won 57 percent of the vote, had 362, according to The Associated Press delegate count. The super delegates _ party leaders and politicians who automatically hold seats as convention delegates _ are not bound to support a presidential candidate based on results of the primaries or caucuses. And while the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has no `` winner-take-all'' states, it does have a few states in which direct election of delegates or `` winner-take-more'' systems are used. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> used both of those aspects of the party's rules to give him the margin of delegates he needed to clinch the Democratic presidential nomination. He also intensively sought support from super delegates, often making telephone calls to them himself. Currently, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has 2,384 delegates overall while <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has 1,132. The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign supported the rules changes, but <PERSON> Tad </PERSON> <PERSON> Devine </PERSON>, director of delegate selection for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, said it was not being done to buy peace with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` Hardly,'' <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> said. `` I think it represents a compromise on the part of both campaigns. It reflects a spirit of cooperation and good will.'' The harmony between the two campaigns meant that the party's Rules Committee meeting this weekend was being cut from two days to one and probably would issue no dissenting reports when its business was finished, <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> said Both campaigns said the negotiations had been going on for several days and stretched into the early hours of Saturday morning. However, occasional snags were still being worked out on some issued during the Rules Committee meeting, as a dozen or so representatives of the campaigns talked in a tight huddle at the back of the room. The 186-member committee approved the rules changes on Saturday without dissent, but the proposals still need to be ratified by the full convention next month in order to take effect for the 1992 presidential campaign. `` Though adoption of this proposal does n't put us in the promised land, it puts us further down the road,'' said <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Bracy </PERSON>, a committee member and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporter from <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, of reducing the strength of super delegates. Rep. <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, D-Ky., kept the metaphor: `` This may not be the promised land, but it does represent some milk and honey. <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> did use the current system to his advantage but still would have won the nomination even if the proposed rules changes were in place. `` I do n't deny that we took a look at the delegate selection process in 1988 and developed strategies based on the way the process is structured,'' <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> said. Under the proposed changes, the number of super delegates would be reduced to 394 by denying automatic delegate status to most members of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Automatic delegate status would be reserved for Democratic governors, most members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and top two party leaders in each state and the party's national officers The system would return to rules used in 1984, when <ORGANIZATION> DNC </ORGANIZATION> members had priority for seats at the convention but had to compete for them and had to declare a presidential preference. Super delegates currently represent about 15 percent of the delegates to the convention. Under the proposed rules, that would be cut to about 10 percent. In addition, states such as <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, which picked their national convention delegates directly from the primary ballot, would be compelled to adopt systems to award the delegates proportionally. Another handful of states, including <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, award extra delegates to the candidate receiving the most votes in their primaries, and those systems, too, would have to be changed in four years. The agreement also called for nudging states toward picking new <ORGANIZATION> DNC </ORGANIZATION> members based on whom they support for president and in proportion to results of the primary or caucus in that state. States adopting this rule would be allowed to name one extra member apiece to the <ORGANIZATION> DNC </ORGANIZATION>. In other business Saturday, the committee voted to recognize the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> as a state, giving Mayor <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> an automatic seat at the 1988 convention as a governor. The committee, without debate, named <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> as permanent chairman of this year's national convention. No mention was made of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ethics committee investigation of some of <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s financial dealings.
