<HEAD>Sakharov Speaks Out for Monument To Stalin's Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dissident <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> joined former political prisoners and intellectuals at a rally Saturday to demand a monument to victims of <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>. It was <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s first appearance at a street rally in more than a decade. At another demonstration, about 200 people shouted `` Freedom! Freedom!'' and ignored police orders to disperse. Police detained at least three people. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, the Nobel Prize-winning physicist who spent seven years in exile for speaking out against the Soviet government, told 600 people in north <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> that a monument to <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s victims was essential to remembering the country's `` tragic history.'' The rally joined intellectuals who had been jailed or banished from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> during the rule of former Soviet leader <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> and those who are still trying to get their works past conformist censors. Flanked by a sign showing <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> on a big black boot and warning `` He is still dangerous,'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> told a silent crowd that `` if we have a memorial, we have to think of everybody who died, in the repression, of hunger ... everybody was a victim.'' Later, at <LOCATION> Pushkin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> in the center of the city, a jostling crowd of 200 refused to allow police to break up a demonstration by the alternative political party, <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. They applauded a man who held up a sign saying `` No to the political police. Break up the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, 67, said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s sad past was symbolized by the December 1986 death in jail of <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Marchenko </PERSON>, a fellow member of a group monitoring human rights in the 1970s. <PERSON> Marchenko </PERSON>'s death is thought by some to have hastened the decision by Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> two weeks later to allow <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Yelena </PERSON> <PERSON> Bonner </PERSON>, to return to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> from their exile in the closed city of <LOCATION> Gorky </LOCATION>. Others who spoke at the rally included former political prisoners <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Kovalev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lev </PERSON> <PERSON> Timofeyev </PERSON>, film director <PERSON> Elem </PERSON> <PERSON> Klimov </PERSON>, historian <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Afanasyev </PERSON> and writers <PERSON> Ales </PERSON> <PERSON> Adamovich </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Karyakin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Karyakin </PERSON> told reporters that the rally `` was a beginning. It was important that there were many young people there.'' A group of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members and non-party intellectuals have collected 30,000 signatures on a petition to a nationwide party conference to approve a monument to the millions killed in <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s purges. The conference begins Tuesday. Groups in the Baltic republic of <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> and in the Siberian city of <LOCATION> Chita </LOCATION> have campaigned for such a monument. <PERSON> Klimov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Afanasyev </PERSON> are delegates to the conference and accepted the petition Saturday, promising to raise the issue of a memorial if they are allowed to speak at the 5,000-delegate forum. <PERSON> Timofeyev </PERSON> called for greater openness about the extent of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s purges and proposed that <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>'s chronicle of Soviet prisons, `` The <LOCATION> Gulag </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Archipelago </LOCATION>,'' be published in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>'s appearance at the rally marked the first time he has taken part in a street protest since he and his wife campaigned for freedom outside dissidents' trials in the 1970s. <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> was exiled to <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> in January 1980 for speaking out against the Soviet intervention in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. About an hour after the anti-Stalin rally, which was held with official approval, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> tried to hold a demonstration on <LOCATION> Pushkin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. Police did not intervene at first but later detained <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Mityunov </PERSON> and at least two other people, prompting a shoving match with the crowd of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> supporters and onlookers. A rally staged by another group, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, was then allowed to go ahead, apparently because they back official policies and are not challenging the monopoly of the Communist party. Police tried to break up the demonstrations by throwing up a cordon dividing them, shouting at citizens to move along and waiting for the rest to disperse gradually. <PERSON> Mityunov </PERSON> said earlier the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, which was set up in May, held a sanctioned meeting for about four hours with 1,000 participants in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> Friday.
