<HEAD>Yeast Infection Remedy Nearly Burns Down House, Authorities Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST JORDAN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman following a newspaper story's advice to yeast infection sufferers tossed her underpants in the microwave and sparked a fire, authorities say Firefighters rushed to the woman's home in this south <LOCATION> Salt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> community of 27,000 on Friday morning and quickly extinguished the flames, but not before her microwave oven was destroyed and a nearby wall scorched, said County Fire Chief <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Berry </PERSON>. <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said when the embarassed woman explained how the fire started, firefighters were hard-pressed not to laugh. `` It's one of those things that ` Just when you think you've seen everything ...,''' <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said. However, <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said the incident's humorous side was tempered by its potential for developing into a serious fire if it had not quickly been extinguished. There were no injuries. <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said the woman, who was not identified, decided to `` cook'' her underpants after reading a news service article in a local paper quoting <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> obstetrics and gynecology researchers as saying the bacteria responsible for yeast infections can be killed in a microwave oven in five minutes on the high-power setting. The article emphasized the process only works on cotton underpants, and also recommended the underwear be freshly laundered and slightly damp. The woman was certain the underwear that caught on fire was 100 percent cotton, but fire officials believe they were probably of an artificial material. If the underpants were indeed cotton, the elastic material may have been to blame, they said. <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said that after seeing what happened to the woman's kitchen, he could not recommend the microwave process `` I just would n't do it,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> article said yeast bacteria can also be killed by soaking or boiling underwear in bleach, or by ironing. Common detergents will not kill the bacteria. Antibiotics can fight the actual yeast infection, but women tend to become reinfected, possibly from wearing contaminated underwear, the article said.
