<HEAD>Doctors To Debate Proposals On AIDS, Medicaid Reform At AMA
Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Doctors will debate proposals for battling AIDS, overhauling Medicaid and training a new type of bedside hospital worker this week at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s annual policymaking convention. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION>, which convenes Sunday, also plan to discuss a proposed ban on selling plastic handguns, a move to put warning labels on alcoholic beverages and the association's stand on mercy killing. The meeting, which runs through Thursday, is expected to attract up to 2,000 doctors from across the country. The 420 delegates represent the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION>'s 295,000 members and act as a legislature, setting policy for the nation's largest organization of physicians. The delegates will receive more than 75 reports on problems ranging from child pornography to the health hazards of clove cigarettes. They also will consider at least 155 resolutions on such issues as the health risks of tanning parlors and ways to revamp the nation's <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> health insurance system for the elderly. `` AIDS, of course, is the biggest threatening health problem in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> president Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hotchkiss </PERSON>, a surgeon from <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said last week. `` There is still considerable debate that I think will take place over the issue of testing.'' One resolution, proposed by a group of delegates from <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, recommends requiring state and local health departments to contact the sexual partners of anyone who tests positive for the AIDS virus. The proposal also recommends that all immigrants and inmates be tested for the virus and calls for a national catastrophic health insurance program for AIDS victims and legislation to protect them from discrimination. The <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trustees </ORGANIZATION> is proposing a major overhaul of Medicaid, the nation's program for helping the poor pay for medical care. An <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> report says the program, administered by state governments, is fraught with `` severe inequities.'' Its calls for expanding Medicaid to cover an additional 27 million people at or below the poverty level now excluded because eligibility varies from state to state. A battle may erupt over the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> trustees' proposal to help offset the nationwide shortage of nurses by creating a new class of hospital workers to provide some bedside care to patients. Several nurses associations oppose the plan to create licensed `` registered care technologists.'' Under the plan, high school graduates could begin caring for patients as assistant technologists with two months' training. They could become basic technologists with an additional seven months' training and advanced technologists after nine more months of study. Their duties would include bathing patients, giving out medication and changing bandages. `` This is in no way a substitute for nurses,'' <PERSON> Hotchkiss </PERSON> said. `` It is in addition to nurses.'' Also up for debate are resolutions calling on the <ORGANIZATION> AMA </ORGANIZATION> to oppose so-called mercy killing or euthanasia by doctors and `` refrain from publishing articles which involve the taking of human life'' without stating the group's position. The Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> was criticized earlier this year when it published an article by an unidentified doctor describing how he ended the life of a terminally ill cancer patient.
