<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new campaign to get the Equal Rights Amendment passed wo n't be limited to lobbying <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and state legislatures, leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION> said Saturday. The ERA battle also will be fought at Social Security offices, on college campuses and other places where women are treated unfairly, NOW President <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> <PERSON> Yard </PERSON> said during the opening session of the group's national conference. `` We need to invent new tactics to protest inequality,'' <PERSON> Yard </PERSON> told about 500 NOW members. NOW has called on its local chapters to stage sit-ins at Social Security offices to protest unequal distribution of benefits and at college campuses, where women professors have a hard time getting tenure and where predominantly male administrators are insensitive to campus violence against women, she said. `` Our only guarantee against these things is to be included in the Constitution,'' she said. `` We must keep the fire burning and keep those who perpetuate inequality uncomfortable,'' said former NOW president <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> Smeal </PERSON>. `` The way we are going to pass this amendment is not to worry about what people think of us.'' The ERA was approved by only 35 of the necessary 38 states before a 10-year time limit expired in 1982. NOW's new campaign for ERA passage officially begins Thursday with a rally in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The group hopes to give <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> a petition with 100,000 signatures. The group's leaders say the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has been hostile to their cause, so the end of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s term makes the time right for passage of the amendment. Recent national polls indicate as much as 75 percent of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> vote