<HEAD>Family Rejects $50,000 Offer, Seeks $6.5 Million From Air Force</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to recast and to CORRECT in 1st and 6th
grafs pvs that lawyer quoted is not involved in Goldbergs' case,
but has experience in other wrongful death cases. Picks up 9th graf
pvs, `Many of...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BETH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s offer of $ 50,000 to the parents of a woman killed when one of its jets slammed into a hotel is an outrage, says a lawyer who is an expert on wrongful death, but the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> says its offer is consistent with state law. <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> law provides little in the way of damage payments when a single person dies, which the woman's family criticized as discriminatory. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harriet </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> already have rejected the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s offer, which doubled the original $ 25,000 sum, and say they may take the matter to court. They had been seeking $ 6.5 million in damages for the death of their daughter, <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>, 30. She was among 10 people killed Oct. 20 when the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> A-7 fighter jet crashed into the lobby of the <LOCATION> Ramada </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, where she worked. The pilot, who was from <ORGANIZATION> Nellis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, ejected from the craft before it crashed and was not seriously injured. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chesley </PERSON>, a Cincinnati-based lawyer who specializes in multiple death cases, is not involved in the Goldbergs' case but said the $ 50,000 offer was ridiculous. `` Just because someone is n't married does n't mean their life is n't worth anything,'' he said in a telephone interview Friday. `` There's only one way to get a full settlement: Take it to the courthouse.'' Under <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>'s wrongful death law, a court can award damage payments to parents if a minor child dies, and to the spouse or other financial dependents of an adult who dies. However, only medical, funeral and estate administration costs can be collected when an adult dies who had no financial dependents. Many of the jet crash victims had dependent families, but Ms. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> was single. `` Based on <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> law, that's an amount that's consistent in this type of situation,'' said Maj. <PERSON> Derence </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fivehouse </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> aviation litigation section. `` If we did somebody harm, we pay them what we owe them by state law. That's my mandate.'' As of Friday, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> had settled 98 of the 108 claims filed, said <PERSON> Fivehouse </PERSON>. He refused to say what size settlements were being offered to families of other victims. `` Only people with dependents are entitled to love and affection? She was such a vital part of our family,'' <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said of his daughter, the oldest of the couple's three daughters. `` <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> law needs to be changed because our wrongful death law is so archaic,'' <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said. `` I feel we have a moral obligation to pursue it. Nothing in the way of a settlement is going to bring our daughter back.'' <PERSON> Fivehouse </PERSON> said the Goldbergs were given a July 1 deadline to consider the settlement offer so that the proceedings would not stall. After Friday, the family will be sent a letter acknowledging their rejection of the $ 50,000 offer. The Goldbergs then will have six months to continue negotiations or file suit, <PERSON> Fivehouse </PERSON> said. `` It appears that's what they want,'' he added. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said the family would be willing to lower the claim, but plans to file a lawsuit if an agreement is n't reached in the next month. The Goldbergs' $ 6.5 million claim figure was based on the amount of money their daughter would have made during her career, the family's emotional devastation and the cost of psychiatric counseling for Ms. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>'s survivors. Ms. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> was a sales representative at the hotel. <PERSON> Chesley </PERSON> has represented families of victims in the 1980 MGM hotel fire in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, that killed 84 people, and the 1977 <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> Supper Club fire in northern <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> that killed 164. Settlements for the claims in the <ORGANIZATION> MGM </ORGANIZATION> fire ranged from $ 1 million to $ 2 million for single individuals and $ 7 million to $ 9 million for people with dependents, <PERSON> Chesley </PERSON> said.
