<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state of <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> apparently has a claim to five old wooden boats discovered on the bed of the drought-shrunken <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, a lawyer who represents the vessels' four discoverers said Saturday. But if the state does n't claim the boats, which were found last weekend about 100 yards from the river's <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> side, the four <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> men `` would probably have a superior claim over anybody else,'' said attorney <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> <PERSON> Lofton </PERSON>. State Attorney General <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said Saturday that the state would likely pursue clarification of ownership of the boats, which one of the discoverers said may date to the 1840s. `` But it depends on what the value is. It's not their dollar value that's so important, but the historical value,'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said, adding that he was not familiar with the find. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Spears </PERSON> said Saturday that he and three friends found the boats while walking along river bottom that has become exposed and cracked because of the drought that has lowered the river 20 feet. The boats were about a half-mile from the bridge connecting <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, Tenn, <PERSON> Spears </PERSON> said. `` It was a total surprise,'' said <PERSON> Spears </PERSON>, 42, adding that he has long heard tales of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> concealing sunken boats. `` I think this needs to be preserved. It's history.'' The age of the boats has n't been determined, he said. <PERSON> Lofton </PERSON> said his clients also would n't mind `` the possibility of making some money off of it.'' However, the Abandoned Shipwreck Act of 1987, which President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed on April 28, puts boats submerged in navigable waters in possession of the federal government, in trust for the state in which the vessels are found, <PERSON> Lofton </PERSON> said. A state archaeologist who examined the vessels last week did n't seem to think <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> would be interested in preserving them, <PERSON> Lofton </PERSON> said `` That's why I want to read this law,'' <PERSON> Lofton </PERSON> said. If the state decides it does n't want the boats, his clients `` are investigating the possibility of dealing with some sort of salvage company that has the capability of doing this.'' <PERSON> Spears </PERSON> said he and his friends _ <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Suiter </PERSON>, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Samples </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> _ were willing `` to just leave this matter up to time right now,'' to see if the state lays claim to the boats. `` This is very valuable,'' <PERSON> Suiter </PERSON> said. `` We're not out to get somebody to grease our palms. This is something that <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> should be proud of. It could make an archaeological museum that could bring in millions of dollars in tourist traffic.'' The Commercial Appeal at <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> offered a theory Saturday about how the boats sank, quoting two local amateur river historians, <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Marquis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, as saying they may have gone down in a 1918 ice storm. The best-preserved of the five vessels may be a coal barge that dates to the 1880s, the pair said. Columnist <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> also reported that `` veteran river-watchers say the wrecks have been exposed before _ last year, a salvage worker used a torch to cut the metal cleats off one of the boats.'' <PERSON> Suiter </PERSON> discounted the ice storm theory. `` If they had been in this storm, the boats would have been crushed, and they're not,'' he said in a telephone interview.
