<HEAD>Watch Tells Moslems When To Pray</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company has designed a wristwatch that alerts Moslems when it's time to pray and even shows them the direction of the holy city of <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> from 120 cities around the world, a newspaper said Saturday. An alarm sounds 10 minutes before each day's five prayer periods, the English-language Saudi Gazette said. The actual time is dictated by the position of the sun, according to the Koran, <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s holy book, which also decrees that the faithful should face <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> while praying. Traditionally, the five daily prayer calls are made by muezzins, or priests, who summon the faithful from minarets attached to mosques. Nowadays, prayer periods are published by newspapers and broadcast by radio and television stations in Moslem countries. The watch has been developed by <ORGANIZATION> Sysorex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, a computer systems company based in <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> View </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, the newspaper said. The Gazette quoted <PERSON> Abdullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Saadan </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Sysorex </ORGANIZATION> agent in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, as saying the watch communicates in both Arabic and English and gives both Gregorian and <LOCATION> Hijra </LOCATION>, or Islamic calendar, dates. To overcome differences between Moslem scholars over how prayer times should be determined, <PERSON> Saadan </PERSON> said the times programmed into the watch have been approved by several Islamic bodies. The watch comes in various models ranging in price from $ 85 to $ 115, the newspaper said.
