<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The strawberry shortcake was anything but short Saturday as cooking school students put together a 216-foot version of the summertime goodie. `` Rush! Speed! Speed!'' shouted <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, a second-year student at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Culinary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, as teams began building what they hope will be officially recognized as the world's largest strawberry shortcake. First down on the tables were the 31 sheet pans of shortcake cut into 4-inch-wide strips. Next went about 7,200 strawberries, and finally, 18 gallons of whipped cream. `` Step back, I need a picture of this,'' roared <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Wobby </PERSON>, the event's organizer, before the whipped cream went on. He also brought the world its longest dish of maple sugar on snow in <LOCATION> Barre </LOCATION> two years ago, a quarter-mile-long affair. As the students put the finishing touches on their cake, the rain picked up, and the crowd lining the sidewalks rushed to the center of State Street for one, or maybe more, of the 2,400 pieces. The largest strawberry shortcake, according to <PERSON> Wobby </PERSON>'s research, was 6 feet in diameter. By square footage, Saturday's long-and-narrow version was considerably larger, <PERSON> Wobby </PERSON> said There is currently no separate entry in the Guinness Book of World Records for largest strawberry shortcake, but the students are hoping to get recognition. `` It's a good gag,'' <PERSON> Wobby </PERSON> said. `` It's something we'll think start thinking about and say, ` That's impossible.' Then, all of a sudden, the blood just turns on, and we find we have the motivation to do it, and we do it.''
