 The mine-damaged <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> missile frigate <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> was towed out of <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION> Saturday toward a <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> island to be loaded aboard a specially built cargo vessel that will take it back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The 3,600-ton frigate was severely damaged when it hit a submerged Iranian mine April 14. It underwent preliminary repairs at a <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION> shipyard and will be rebuilt in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say. The Mighty Servant 2, a 25,743-ton Dutch cargo ship chartered by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> to carry the <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, was anchored off <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> Nu'ayr island, 60 miles west of <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION>. It was to be partially submerged to allow the frigate to be floated onto its deck. The tricky loading operation was in danger of being delayed by rough seas, gulf-based shipping sources reported, speaking on the condition of anonymity. Three-foot swells were reported off <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> Nu'ayr, they said. <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> photographer <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> English </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, which nearly sank after the mine ripped a 25-foot gash in its hull, `` looked normal'' as it was towed from <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION>'s busy port by the tugboat Tornado. He said the frigate was about 12 miles from its rendezvous with the Mighty Servant 2 when the towline was lost, and the frigate continued under its own auxiliary power. Most of the frigate's 225 crewmen have returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but 30 stayed behind to go home with the ship.