<HEAD>Southern Africa Peace Talks to Resume Next Month</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Delegates to U.S.-mediated peace talks trying to settle southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> conflicts agreed Saturday to sponsor another round next month in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. A communique at the end of two days of talks said the July 11 meeting will be at the `` experts level'' at an undisclosed place in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. It said foreign ministers will not attend. `` Further progress was made, and a plan of work was developed for continuing exchanges at the level of experts to expand on the progress made in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>,'' the communique said. It stated the aim of the negotiations as working `` toward a regional settlement of the conflict in southwestern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' The delegates from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> met Friday and Saturday, seeking a formula to end a 13-year war in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and usher in independence for <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, commonly known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. Earlier talks in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazzaville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Congo </LOCATION>, last month failed to achieve settlement. In sessions Saturday morning and afternoon, the delegates dealt with widely divergent proposals presented Friday on how to resolve the war in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and end South African rule in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, conference sources said. About a dozen leaders of the four delegations worked out communique details in a poolside meeting after full negotiations apparently bogged down in the hotel conference room. The venue for the next talks was apparently the main point at issue. The Angola-Cuba side was said to be opposed to holding the next round in an Afric