<SECOND>AM-Kerouac Memorial,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Memorial Celebrates Roots of Jack Kerouac</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Friends and literary contemporaries of <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerouac </PERSON> reunited Saturday to remember the man who defined the `` beat generation'' of the 1950s. A replay of <PERSON> Kerouac </PERSON>'s reading of the final paragraph of his classic novel `` On the Road'' from a 1959 television show culminated the dedication of a one-acre park commemorating the Lowell-born author. The 90-minute ceremony, attended by about 1,000 people including two of <PERSON> Kerouac </PERSON>'s three wives and poets <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Ginsberg </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferlinghetti </PERSON>, officially opened the first public memorial to <PERSON> Kerouac </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Lowell </LOCATION> and sought to settle past controversy over the project. `` Ultimately, the quality of the work overshadows all the other issues,'' said <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON>. `` One of the fundamental principals of the park is to encourage the free exchange of ideas.'' Some residents had opposed the memorial because of <PERSON> Kerouac </PERSON>'s heavy drinking and itinerant, unconventional lifestyle The $ 100,000 memorial is an arrangement of 3-by-8-foot granite panels bearing 15 passages from most of <PERSON> Kerouac </PERSON>'s 20 books and essays, including the so-called <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> novels `` Doctor Sax'' and `` The Town and the City.'' Previously, the only reference to <PERSON> Kerouac </PERSON> was his small grave marker on the other side of the city. `` I feel very good about this memorial,'' said <PERSON> Ginsberg </PERSON>, who met <PERSON> Kerouac </PERSON> when both were students at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the early 1940s. `` It's so that any kid in the next century can wander in here and be inspired to language and imagination.'' The inscribed p