<HEAD>Death Toll Reaches Seven in Tank Farm Explosion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 UPDATE with Pemex confirming 7 dead, listing 5
hurt, giving possible fire cause. Picks up 6th graf pvs, Two men .
..</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three more workers died Saturday from burns suffered in a fiery explosion at a gasoline supply depot, bringing to seven the number of confirmed dead in the fire, hospital officials said. The government petroleum monopoly <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the tank farm, confirmed that seven men died and said five were injured. It said the blaze may have started when gasoline `` spilled into an area where soldering work was being done.'' Neighborhoods surrounding the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rafael </LOCATION> sales agency in <LOCATION> Guadalupe </LOCATION> filled up once again as thousands of twice-evacuated residents returned home. Firefighters thought they put out the blazes early Friday and most residents went home, only to flee again in panic a short time later when a tank reignited. The <PERSON> Constructora </PERSON> <PERSON> Quiroga </PERSON> y <PERSON> Villarreal </PERSON> company was doing maintenance work on a fire prevention system Thursday when a 2.2 million-gallon gasoline tank exploded and ignited two other tanks. It was the second major fire at a <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> gasoline storage depot in a month. Two men died Saturday of burns at the Hospital 21 in <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardenas </PERSON>, a shift assistant. A third man died Saturday at the city's <LOCATION> Uiversity </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Medellin </PERSON>, an official at the hospital's morgue. Company clerk <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Salas </PERSON> said 13 workers were accounted for after having been reported missing after the blast. A <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> news release Saturday said the fire was extinguished at 3 a.m. and `` the security of the area has been totally re-established.'' Across from the explosion site, life began returning to normal. Young boys rode bicycles outside the depot's cement walls. Others peeked through gaps in the wall to see the charred remains of the tanks. `` It's good to be home,'' said 28-year-old <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> <PERSON> Reymundo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delgado </PERSON>. He said he spent two nights at one of the emergency shelters set up after the disaster. `` The first night I stayed in a cattle stall so I did n't get much sleep. But last night was better,'' he said. One shelter was at the <ORGANIZATION> Guadalupe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exposition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ground </ORGANIZATION>, which houses an annual cattle show and fair. <PERSON> Silvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, 30, who lives across the street from the tanks, said she came home to find milk was sour and meat was spoiled in the refrigerator. `` The electricity was off the whole time and did n't come back on until just after we got home,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> said she was trapped in her house with her mother, sister and nephews for several minutes after the explosion as smoke and fire billowed toward her house. No damage to homes was reported. <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> said it set up a special blast investigation team. The tank farm was temporarily closed for the investigation. Its 23 tanks supplied gasoline and diesel fuel to area gas stations and other users. Witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said they saw the top of one tank rupture outward and then collapse. They said gasoline gushed down the side of the tank and across the ground. The witnesses said they suspected the tank may have ruptured because it was filled far beyond capacity. <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> has said only there was a gas leak in a tank. <LOCATION> Guadalupe </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Adan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> said in an interview that it was his `` obligation'' to ask the state government to relocate the tank farm because it posed a constant hazard. <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> closed down a similar tank farm in <LOCATION> Chihuahua </LOCATION>, capital of the northern state of the same name, a month ago following an explosion and daylong fire. No one died in that accident.
