<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, the last major men-only club for <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s elite, has followed in the tracks of the <ORGANIZATION> Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> and voted to accept women as members, its president said Saturday. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D.H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> said the vote by the club's 15-member governing board was taken Wednesday and members were notified by letters that arrived in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> on Saturday. `` We thought it was an idea whose time had come,'' <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> said. `` The board made a policy change to accept ladies in membership for all categories.'' The vote was taken just four days after <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s private <ORGANIZATION> Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> voted to accept woman and two days after the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upheld a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> law aimed at requiring the admission of women to big, private clubs where important business dealings often occur. <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> refused to discuss any specifics of the vote or the procedures for acceptance into the exclusive 2,200-member club. He said the club's decision to admit women was not based on the <ORGANIZATION> Cosmos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> precedent or other pressures. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Banzhaf </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, a professor at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and an opponent of sex discrimination at priv