<HEAD>Third Baltic Republic Makes Demands For More Autonomy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Intellectuals and Communist officials in the Baltic republic of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> have followed two other republics in demanding more autonomy from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> as this week's party conference approaches, the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> indicated Saturday. The Communist head of the republic of <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>, meanwhile, criticized intellectuals who made radical demands for sovereignty at a stormy meeting of hundreds of writers, artists and scientists this month. A brief report by <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said a rally of about 10,000 people called by a group of intellectuals, The Movement To Support Perestroika, was held in the <LOCATION> Lithuanian </LOCATION> capital of <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION> Friday night. Perestroika refers to <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of economic and political reforms. Several intellectuals and delegates to the party conference addressed the crowd, paying `` great attention to the questions of national culture, language, history and ecology,'' and instructing delegates what to say in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The 19th All-Union Conference of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, scheduled to open Tuesday, will be the first since 1941. Five thousand delegates will attend. A similar meeting in the Estonian capital of <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION> June 17 is reported to have attracted 150,000 people, who cheered speeches demanding the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> turn into a federation of sovereign republics. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> did not say if similar demands were raised at the <LOCATION> Vilnius </LOCATION> meeting. But the <ORGANIZATION> Lithuanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, an emigre group in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said it had learned that a Communist official in <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Algirdas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brazauskas </PERSON>, addressed the meeting, calling for a sovereign <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> and for Lithuanian to be made the official language of the republic. The issue of preserving indigenous language and culture in the Baltic republics has evoked strong emotions as a large number of ethnic Russians and other ethnic groups migrate into the area. The Lithuanian Writers' Union demanded April 4 that dual-language schools be abolished in the republic and that Lithuanians outside the republic's borders be taught in Lithuanian. Ethnic Estonians are now in a minority in their own republic, a fact that is fueling concern about the economic, ecological and other consequences of more than 40 years of Soviet rule. The presence of leading Communist party officials at the rally in <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, as in that in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, indicates that demands in both republics for more genuine autonomy from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> have the official backing of the party hierarchy. However, the head of <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Pugo </PERSON>, condemned some unofficial groups he accused of taking their cue from the West. In an interview published Saturday in the daily <ORGANIZATION> Sotsialiticheskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industriya </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, <PERSON> Pugo </PERSON> said: `` We can not close our eyes to the fact that on the background of perestroika and democratization, recidivists of nationalism and chauvinism are appearing.'' `` Some of the so-called ` informal groups' are trying to draw citizens into various actions under speculative, provocative actions written with the help of Western radio stations,'' <PERSON> Pugo </PERSON> said. He said such groups had been a topic of discussion at a recent plenum of the Latvian <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that followed the June 1 and 2 meeting of intellectuals in <LOCATION> Riga </LOCATION>. Few details of that meeting have been published in the state-run media. A report in the weekly <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> made clear that debates had been stormy. <PERSON> Pugo </PERSON> said that much of the criticism at the intellectuals' meeting `` went ahead without the necessary political analysis. A resolution adopted by the intellectuals and published in <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>'s state-run media June 11 contained a demand to publish the secret protocol of the Soviet-Nazi pact of 1939. The pact ceded the three Baltic republics to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, which sent in troops in 1940.
