<HEAD>AIDS Precautions By Health Care Workers Cause Shortage of Medical
Gloves</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to CORRECT to protect sted prevent.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Precautions taken by health care workers to protect themselves from the AIDS virus have led to a shortage of the latex and vinyl gloves used in the medical profession. It is difficult to pinpoint the degree of the shortage because manufacturers are reluctant to release production figures and such numbers are not available from industry groups or the government. But there is general agreement that availability has sharply declined in the past year since federal health officials urged health care professionals to take increased care to protect themselves from disease organisms that can be transmitted through body fluids. `` There does seem to be a shortage of gloves in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said Dr. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, which regulates the medical glove industry. `` The glove industry is continuing to gear up the production and marketing of gloves to meet the increased demand.'' The sharp and relatively sudden increase in glove use put a pinch on manufacturers' capacity, said <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Baxter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Deerfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, a major producer of medical gloves. `` The immediate cause was probably the encouragement of the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, urging doctors and dentists to glove up whenever they come in contact with a patient's body fluids,'' <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> said. `` For many health care workers, that was all the motivation they needed to glove up. `` Our demand has doubled in the last two years.'' <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Leebaw </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, said his company's glove manufacturing plant in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, has been operating 24 hours a day for more than a year and is planning to add more production equipment. Also, he said, the company has canceled glove orders from non-medical customers. `` The demand has increased quite a bit in connection with the AIDS problem and the concern in general with disease transmission,'' <PERSON> Leebaw </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> said the shortage is mainly a matter of production capacity, rather than a shortage of the materials needed to make the gloves. Latex, the glove of choice for surgeons, is made from rubber, while vinyl gloves are totally synthetic. <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> last year constructed a new glove plant in <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> and is planning another facility there, <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> said. The company also has four <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plants and three in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, said the hospital has felt the shortage, though it has not reached the point where medical service would be threatened. Instead, she said, it has more often been a problem of convenience, with <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> personnel sometimes not able to get the type or size of glove they want. `` But we have not had any problems that would have resulted in a slowdown or shutdown in service,'' she said. Because <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> is an established hospital, its list of vendors is long and thus the facility has several sources of gloves, Ms. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. But its purchasers have had to work hard to make sure the hospital is adequately stocked. The <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> said gloves should be used whenever an individual might come in contact with a patient's blood, which poses the greatest threat for transmission of the virus that causes AIDS and the hepatitis B virus. Gloves also were advised for protection from numerous other body fluids. <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> said he expects demand for gloves to remain high, though it probably will level off at some point. `` I do n't think we'll get the sudden, sharp increase again,'' <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> said. `` Everyone who needs to know about gloving up knows now.''
