<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A magnetic storm expected to affect global communications and electric power transmission on Monday may be less intense than originally thought, scientists said Saturday. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> warned Friday about the storm after the largest solar flare in four years exploded from the sun. But <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION> duty forecaster <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Doggett </PERSON> said Saturday he had amended his forecast. `` We had expected the arrival of energetic protons from the flare and they did not arrive yet, which makes me suspect that the amount of energy put out by the flare was not as great as previously expected,'' he said. `` Based on that, I'm not expecting as large of a geomagnetic disturbance.'' Mild proton radiation associated with the solar flare had been expected to reach orbiting spacecraft Saturday. <PERSON> Doggett </PERSON> said the level of flare activity was expected to remain high, but its effects on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> probably would be felt less strongly than initially predicted. For instance, the magnetic storm had been expected to push <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>'s auroras away from the poles, making the northern lights visible as far south as the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Doggett </PERSON> said Saturday, however, that `` the likelihood of seeing aurora displays wo n't be very high, in the continental <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at least.'' He said disturbances to electrical power transmission also probably will be less than expected. Officials ca n't forecast the magnetic storm with certainty, <PERSON> Doggett </PERSON> said, and the possibility for a strong storm remains as hot gases and electrically charged particles emitted by the solar flare hit Earth's magnetic field. The phenomenon does not directly threaten life on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. However, it can disrupt shortwave and other communications, including contact between airliners and ground controllers and long-distance phone calls. The magnetic storm also could cause errors in the orbits of some satellites.
