<HEAD>GOP Nominates Foreign Policy Expert for U.S. Senate Run</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENBELT, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State Republican leaders Saturday named conservative foreign policy expert <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keyes </PERSON> as the party's candidate for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat held by Democrat <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarbanes </PERSON>, who is seeking a third term <PERSON> Keyes </PERSON> replaces businessman <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Blair </PERSON>, who won the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nomination in the March primary but surprised party officials earlier this month when he announced he would withdraw from the race because of unspecified personal and business pressures. The special convention of the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> selected <PERSON> Keyes </PERSON> over <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Zarwell </PERSON> by a vote of 106-4. <PERSON> Zarwell </PERSON> had finished well back in a crowded Republican primary this spring. In an acceptance speech, <PERSON> Keyes </PERSON>, 37, pledged a vigorous campaign that would carry a message that `` freedom works.'' In earlier remarks to the convention, <PERSON> Keyes </PERSON> outlined a philosophy that government programs are only effective when they empower individual citizens to solve their own problems. <PERSON> Keyes </PERSON> decried what he said was the emergence in the 1960s of a new liberal philosophy that encourages `` the lie that freedom is a choice with no responsibility.'' <PERSON> Keyes </PERSON>' remarks were well received by the party faithful and seemed, at least for a time, to heal a bitter split in the party. `` Keyes' inspiring vision for <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>'s future, plus his rousing pledge to campaign hard to capture the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat, really fired up the convention,'' said <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> state Chairman <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Flemi