<HEAD>Cuban Production Fell in 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Domestic commercial production in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> fell by 3.2 percent in 1987 because of depreciation of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar, reduced imports and a poor sugar crop, the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> government news agency <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Latina </ORGANIZATION> reported Saturday. In monetary terms, mercantile production was $ 491.8 million less than in 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cuba </ORGANIZATION> said in a report cited by the news agency. The dispatch, monitored in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, cited the depreciation of the dollar against other currencies and government restrictions against imports from free-market economies for the decline in the mercantile sector. It also blamed a drought that for the third straight year reduced the sugar harvest, severely affected other crops and lowered cattle production. Sugar production, which <PERSON> Prensa </PERSON> <PERSON> Latina </PERSON> called `` the basis of the life of the country,'' fell 3.9 percent last year. The sector's poor performance accounted for 13 percent of the drop in economic production, it said Non-sugar production suffered a 3.1 percent drop in 1987 because of a shortage of foreign reserves needed to purchase supplies from abroad, the bank report said. Imports dropped 20 percent from 1986, it said. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s total foreign trade in 1987 was unchanged from the previous year. The Prensa Latina dispatch did not provide a figure. The country's foreign trade deficit shrank by 1.5 percent, it said. A severe dollar shortage forced the government to ask Western creditor nations this year to reschedule its foreign debt over 15 years and ask for a 5-year grace period, according to a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> document made public in March. The document, released by <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a conservative human rights group, listed <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s debt to Western creditors at $ 5.5 billion. World oil sales are conducted in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has been sending proceeds of Soviet oil export sales to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, and so the dollar's decline in value has hit <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s foreign reserves. The decline in mercantile production `` did not affect the quality of life of the population,'' the National bank report said. Life expectancy for men on the island nation was 72.66 years, and 76.1 years for women in 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Latina </ORGANIZATION> said.
