<HEAD>Foreign Ministers Discuss Latin American Economic Integration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAXACA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The foreign ministers from seven leading Latin American nations opened a weekend meeting Saturday aimed at increasing regional economic and trade ties. The Group of Eight _ including <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> _ also will draw up an agenda for a summit meeting of their presidents in the fall at the beach resort of <LOCATION> Punta </LOCATION> <LOCATION> del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Este </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>. Only <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is absent. Its role will be discussed Monday at a continuation of the meeting in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, 300 miles north of <LOCATION> Oaxaca </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> was suspended from the group at its last meeting in February, shortly after military leader Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> was indicted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> engineered the ouster of President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> after <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> tried to fire him. A <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> statement confirmed that Foreign Minister <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> will be present at the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> session, which also will include a review of the Central American situation. The meeting in <LOCATION> Oaxaca </LOCATION>, a picturesque colonial city in southern <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, is intended mostly to explore ways of trying to build a Latin American common market, a project which has been discussed for more than two decades. Recent efforts by <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> indicate a renewed interest in a common market or free trade zone. The three countries last year signed accords breaking down trade barriers and increasing trade among them. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> have shown signs of interest in the idea of reviving Latin American trade partnership, spurred mostly by their huge foreign debts which are making dollars increasingly scarce. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is building a huge pipeline for the Argentine government. `` Integration is one of the issues we will discuss with great confidence and a great sense of realism,'' <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> del </PERSON> <PERSON> Castillo </PERSON>, secretary of the Latin American Economic System, told reporters upon his arrival in <LOCATION> Oaxaca </LOCATION> on Friday night. `` We are convinced that the solution to our problems will not come from outside, we have to seek it ourselves.'' His multigovernment regional organization has been doing studies on the project. <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Londono </PERSON>, a representative from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, called the meeting `` very important, because for the first time the directors of the organizations of Latin American integration -LRB- studies -RRB- will be among us.'' <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> formed the Contradora group in 1983 in a so-far unsuccessful effort to find negotiated solutions to the Central American conflicts in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> joined the Contadora group three years ago. They since have become known as the Group of Eight and met in the most extensive presidential summit in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in more than 20 years last November in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> coastal resort of <LOCATION> Acapulco </LOCATION>.
