<HEAD>Thousands Converge on Site Where Apparition Was Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tens of thousands of Roman Catholics from many lands converged on <LOCATION> Medjugorje </LOCATION> on Saturday to celebrate the seventh anniversary of a reported apparition of the <ORGANIZATION> Virgin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency said. <LOCATION> Medjugorje </LOCATION>, a village in central <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, has become a religious shrine since 1981, when six children _ four boys and two irls _ said they saw the <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> while they were tending sheep on nearby hills. Although the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> never formally accepted the <LOCATION> Medjugorje </LOCATION> shrine, the pilgrims, including sick and disabled people, have been gathering each day in the village to watch for the <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> to reappear. They also want to listen to the six Yugoslavs, now adults, communicate with the <PERSON> Virgin </PERSON> <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>. About 10 million people from <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> and abroad have visited the site. `` A large number of today's visitors came from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>,'' said the state-operated <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> agency. Communist <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> has a reputation for relative liberalism, but the idea of thousands of Christians turning the village into a religious shrine initially caused great apprehension among authorities. After six years of hesitation, however, state-run companies decided to try to capitalize on the influx of foreign visitors. A modern hotel complex, along with hundreds of private inns, were built to accommodate an unprecedented tourist boom in the region.
