<FIRST>u a AM-LawyersCommittee 1stLd-Writethru a0579 06-25 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lawyers Committee, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0579,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>20 Years of Lawyering for Progess in Civil Rights</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 8th graf, ``A Harvard ...,'' to UPDATE
with Kennedy's speech to committee; picks up 9th graf, ``The
committee's ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some days, <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> works for the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>. Other days, she opposes it. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> and other attorneys at <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s big law firms have been moving back and forth across that fence for two decades. On one side, they butter their bread. On the other, they soothe their souls. The committee, which celebrated its 20th anniversary Saturday, assigns lawyers to represent black, Asian and Hispanic clients in discrimination cases. The lawyers volunteer their time, and 26 <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> law firms donate most of the committee's $ 400,000 annual budget. Those same firms, however, also represent many of the powerful organizations and individuals that the committee sues. To be sure, the lawyers follow ethical guidelines intended to prevent conflicts of interest, and no firm represents both sides in a single case. But the irony of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s top lawyers and law firms donating time and money to take on their establishment clients is obvious _ and the committee's staff is n't shy about discussing it. `` We've been successful by being part of the establishment, but at the same time being an organization that continually challenges the establishment,'' said <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnwine </PERSON>, the committee's executive director `` It has its awkward and also its amusing moments,'' said <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, who is simultaneously suing the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> on behalf of the committee and defending the city's <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sewer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> against a suit filed for the committee by another lawyer. A <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> graduate and partner in the firm of <ORGANIZATION> Sullivan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Worcester </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said she likes taking cases for the committee because they are often class-action suits involving `` meaty'' constitutional issues. `` Twenty-five years ago, there was no Civil Rights Act, no Voting Rights Act, no Fair Housing Act, and precious little civil rights,'' Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., told the group at its anniversary dinner Saturday night `` The Lawyers' Committee can point with pride to your indispensable role in the writing of these laws _ and your equally indispensible role in securing their strong enforcement.'' The committee's best-known suit was probably the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> school desegregation case of 1972, which resulted in the court order for racial integration of the city's schools. But the group also has challenged hiring practices in the police and fire departments. It brought a 1976 federal case that established the obligation of employers to maintain a work environment free of racial or sexual harassment. It has represented victims of racially motivated violence. And it has been particularly active in the fair housing arena. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, a partner in the firm of <ORGANIZATION> Palmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION>, said there are some self-interested reasons why old-line firms may support the committee _ particularly recruiting. `` Whatever people may say about pin-striped lawyers, there are still a lot of people who go to law school motivated in part by a desire to bring about social change,'' he said. `` You can often recruit better lawyers to your firm because they know they'll have the opportunity to get involved in civil rights cases.'' But, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said, most of the city's big law firms also recognize that it is `` in everyone's interest'' to keep <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> `` the most civilized city in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' and that `` part of being civilized is not discriminating on the basis of race.'' Formally named the <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Under </ORGANIZATION> the Law, the group was formed by the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in the wake of the riots following the assassination of the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> in 1968. It is one of several regional chapters of the national <ORGANIZATION> Lawyers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, which had been established in 1963 at the instigation of President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and Attorney General <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> `` At a time in which there's been a loss of momentum on civil rights issues in the public sector _ under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration in particular _ the lawyers' committee has maintained the momentum of the'60s and'70s,'' said Superior Court Judge <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Flannery </PERSON>, who worked for the committee before going on the bench in 1984. `` Its commitment is more than lip service, more than just rhetorical,'' he added. `` They have jumped in and done the actual, nitty-gritty legal work, at considerable risk of unpopularity.''
