<HEAD>Newspaper Probe Finds Elderly Are Victims of Prescription Blunders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two million elderly Americans become ill or die each year because of reactions to drugs often prescribed unnecessarily and sometimes taken in potentially deadly doses, a newspaper reported Sunday. The <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> said it found through a five-month investigation in 13 states that many institutionalized elderly are given mind-altering drugs, that thousands have died after getting wrong dosages and that others were used as guinea pigs in drug experiments. The newspaper said in the first installment of a seven-day series it had found that about one in every seven doses of medicine the elderly receive are in error. Of the $ 9 billion people over 65 spend annually on prescription drugs, about $ 2 billion is considered unnecessary, the Republic said, citing federal records. Officials have estimated the total health-care bill for wrongly medicating the elderly at $ 21 billion a year, the newspaper said. Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Aging, called the problem `` a national outrage. ` Those figures are staggering,'' Pepper said. `` It shows how callous some people are regarding the elderly. All they want to do is placate them until they pass away.'' In <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, some nursing homes have made medication errors more than half the time they give drugs, the Republic said. The national <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> considers a 5 percent error rate acceptable. The newspaper said it also found that: _ Some doctors and drug companies around the country used elderly patients as test subjects for experiments, sometimes involving new, unlicensed drugs, without obtaining the patients' informed consent _ Numerous medical studies conducted since the mid-1970s show the aged have been improperly given tranquilizers, hypnotic drugs and potent antipsychotic drugs that left thousands severely ill, hospitalized or dead. _ Many thousands of elderly who are overmedicated fall, suffering debilitating, sometimes fatal injuries. _ Most medical schools have inadequately trained doctors, particularly in geriatric pharmacology and geriatrics. _ Many doctors do not want to treat the elderly, nor do they find it financially desirable to care for them in nursing homes because of strict federal limitations on Medicare reimbursements. _ Despite congressional orders five years ago to do so, many drug manufacturers still have not tested most of their drugs on the elderly to determine effects and have failed to recognize the need for a category specifying geriatric doses in labeling and package inserts. The Republic also said doctors are ignorant of the extent of medication-related deaths partly because autopsies are rarely performed on the elderly, leaving physicians often to guess the cause. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Goddard </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, who founded the senior citizens segment of the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Luke </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> chemical-dependency unit in <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> in 1974, estimated that 30 percent of the patients he met in 10 years directing the program were addicted to prescription medications. Most were women. `` That is the drug problem with older people,'' said <PERSON> Goddard </PERSON>, 84. `` We do n't take heroin or cocaine. It would be a news story if we did.''
