<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 30 women removed their shirts in a city park and bared their breasts for several hours to protest a state law allowing men, but not women, to remove their shirts in public. It was the third year in a row for the protest, which is becoming an annual rite of summer. `` We intend to continue this until the law is changed,'' said <PERSON> Ramona </PERSON> <PERSON> Santorelli </PERSON>, a protest organizer. `` This is a day to celebrate the acceptance of women going shirtless.'' Bare-chested women played softball and volleyball, and lounged in the sun at <LOCATION> Genesee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Santorelli </PERSON> launched the effort three years ago after a security guard ordered her to put a shirt on while she was sunbathing in an uncrowded city park. The first protest in 1986 attracted a large crowd of gawkers and hecklers who taunted the seven women who removed their shirts and were arrested. The women were acquitted of misdemeanor charges, but their victory was a partial one. Judge <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Walz </PERSON> ruled it was permissible for the women to remove their shirts in public as a form of protest, but said it would be illegal for any other reason. Last year, about 25 women bared their breasts and enjoyed their picnic without interruption from onlookers or the police. Saturday was a repeat of that experience. The event was a bit befuddling for <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Massaquoi </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Liberia </LOCATION> attending a family reunion in a picnic shelter near the topless women. `` Looks to me what you have over there is Western society degenerating,'' <PERSON> Massaquoi </PERSON> said. `` In <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, this is the custom and native way and you can understand it. But what's good for <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is not necessarily good for <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>.''
