s to keep the strategic waterway open, but have retained separate commands. Last month, <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> said Soviet proposals to form a single U.N.-sponsored task force in the gulf `` would be very difficult to put together ... in practical terms.'' The British, Dutch and Belgian governments have been engaged in discussions `` for some time'' about bringing their minesweepers under joint control, the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said, speaking on condition of anonymity in keeping with British practice. The planned withdrawal of a Belgian command vessel from the area July 1 `` strengthened the case for full co-operation,'' the spokesman said. The new task force will patrol the area north of <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>, the spokesman said, under the protection of a destroyer and two frigates from the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s Armilla patrol. The operation is code-named `` Calendar'' after the successful mine clearance of the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>' Scheldt estuary after World War II. A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Jane </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which produces the authoritative `` <PERSON> Jane </PERSON>'s Fighting Ships,'' said vessels from the Western navies in the region currently number 52. There are 27 American vessels in the gulf and north <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.
