<SECOND>AM-Bishops Conference,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS, Women's Issues Top Agenda At Gathering Of Bishops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLLEGEVILLE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three peace groups planned an all-night prayer vigil as about 250 <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops gathered Friday for a national conference to consider AIDS, women's issues and the morality of nuclear war. On Saturday the bishops are to debate and vote on a report about the morality of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear policy. <PERSON> Pax </PERSON> <PERSON> Christi </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Benedictines </ORGANIZATION> for Peace from <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Collegeville </LOCATION>, and Franciscans for Peace of Little Falls planned the vigil to coincide with discussions on the morality of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear policy. The report on nuclear policy is the result of two years of work by a bishops' committee commissioned as a follow-up to their 1983 peace pastoral. The committee is recommending that its `` conditional acceptance'' of nuclear deterrence be retained, according to a pre-conference news release. The bishops received a letter Friday from Gen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrahamson </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Initiative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, who wrote of his fears that some of conference's recommendations might be based on inaccurate information. `` Specifically, I wish to challenge some of the arguments which attempt to substantiate the final recommendations ... which, if left unchallenged, will certainly perpetuate the cloud of misunderstanding that surrounds SDI and its promise of a moral deterrence to nuclear war,'' he said. The session at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in south-central <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> is the fourth meeting in six years of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION>. About 280 of the bishops also discussed Friday the first draft of a pastoral letter on the concerns of women in church and society. `` It is one thing to read a report on the reactions of women to the first draft of this pastoral,'' the Most Rev. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Imesch </PERSON> told the conference. `` It is quite another thing to hear women voice their concerns personally. `` The mere fact that men were writing a pastoral letter about women caused considerable skepticism for a number of people,'' said <PERSON> Imesch </PERSON>, bishop of the <LOCATION> Joliet </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, diocese. `` We dared not presume what women thought or felt.'' The 100-page document is the result of three years work by a committee of six bishops and seven women. The committee met with 25 national <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> women's oganizations and heard from 75,000 women who participated in forums in 100 dioceses, and at 60 colleges and 45 military bases across the country. The document also explores <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> tradition and proposes ways of addressing the concerns within the framework of the teachings of the church. A majority of women love the church, the report said. Many are comfortable with their treatment in the church, but many others want more participation. Some saw their exclusion from the priesthood as unjust. The document does n't address the issue of the ordination of women to the priestood, but it calls for a study of allowing women to become deacons. The majority praised the church's stance on abortion, but many questioned its teaching on contraception. The document, which calls sexism a sin, also insists that men take their responsibility in the areas of sexuality, procreation and parenthood seriously. After hearing the concerns of other bishops, <PERSON> Imesch </PERSON> said the document might need a major revision but he still hoped the bishops could act upon it as scheduled for their November 1989 meeting.
</TEXT>
