<FIRST>a a BC-TickerTalk Adv27   06-25 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 27,0716</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday, June 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>Parched Farmland and Withering Crops Spawn Search For `Drought
Stocks'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After viewing the drought as a reason to shun stocks, some strategists see it as a chance to buy into companies that could profit by selling products ranging from hybrid seeds to well-drilling rigs. Food processors, fertilizer makers, seed distributors, farm equipment manufacturers and irrigation companies are getting increased scrutiny as possible investment opportunities because of the drought, which has withered much of this year's crops and sent corn, wheat and soybean prices soaring. The thinking is that farmers will have to invest heavily for the 1989 harvest and that food companies will enjoy better profits from higher prices. For example, Pioneer Hi-Bred International, one of the largest hybrid seed-corn producers, has attracted some attention as a possible beneficiary, partly because of its advanced research into drought-resistant strains. `` These people have been through this before, and are exceedingly familiar with drought conditions,'' said <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON>, a stock strategist at the <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, office of the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Newhard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` They are by far the superior company in this business.'' Freight-hauling companies, especially railroads and truckers, also appear well-positioned to exploit the barge backups on the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, which have drastically reduced the amount of grain shipped to food processors. `` Certainly the transportation aspect of the agriculture market is going to be a winner here, because most farmers are going to be very quick to get their product to market,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbanel </PERSON>, a futures expert at <ORGANIZATION> Gruntal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` If somebody has a better system for transporting grains, it's certainly a moneymaking situation.'' A projected shortage of soybeans also has some Wall Street analysts puzzling out the profitable opportunities. Soybeans are getting heavy attention because they are used in a wide range of products unrelated to food, from unleaded gasoline to cosmetics. A few strategists are even recommending poultry companies. Their argument goes like this: Cattle farmers will be forced to slaughter their herds this year because they ca n't afford to feed them. This will create a short-term beef and pork glut, but by next year acute shortages are certain. With meat prices soaring then, more consumers may switch to cheaper chicken. Others are focusing on large fast-food chains that will likely benefit from higher food prices. <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, for example, has been touted by some brokers recently, because it is expected to get increased royalties linked to higher sales revenue from its franchised restaurants. Wall Street initially seized on the drought as a sell signal because it implies sharply higher inflation, which theoretically raises pressure on the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to hike interest rates and thus erodes the comparative value of stocks. But as other evidence has emerged that inflation remains tame, the drought theme has been transformed into an obscure form of good news in the stock market. Some investment strategists see it as the vehicle for companies to lock in greater profit margins by raising prices now. `` In classic supply-demand fashion, commodity prices could fall next year,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bierbusse </PERSON>, an analyst who follows cereal companies for the investment firm of <ORGANIZATION> A.G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edwards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Sons in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>. `` But you and I both know that cereal prices do n't go down.'' Others, however, have n't flocked to the drought theme. They say the drought could hurt food companies, especially those lacking long-term commitments to buy grain at pre-drought prices. They also say the disaster could ruin fragile rural economies and will clearly spill into other areas. `` There's going to be some impact,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Tiritilli </PERSON>, vice president and director of research at <ORGANIZATION> Rodman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Renshaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` Retailers and banks could get hurt. A farmer who does n't have crops ca n't pay loans back. Whatever the ultimate outcome of the drought on Wall Street's collective thinking, some believe it will be short-lived, soon to be displaced by another significant economic event `` The attention span on Wall Street is about 30 minutes,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sobel </PERSON>, a market historian and author. `` If it rains tomorrow, they'll forget about it completely.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday June 27</NOTE>
