<HEAD>Child Labor Again a Problem in China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Child labor, widespread in old <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, is on the rise again and is worrying Communist authorities. The official media report the problem is most severe in the countryside, where the government's new economic reforms encourage private farming and small rural factories. Young children, mostly girls, often are taken out of school to work on farms or factories to add to family incomes. Another reason cited is a lack of funds for rural education. When they took over <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1949, the Communists sought to eliminate child labor and raise literacy rates. They claim to have lowered illiteracy rates from 80 percent when they took over to 20 percent now. The seriousness with which child labor now is viewed is indicated in a series of recent articles in the official press. The weekly Liaowang -LRB- Outlook -RRB-, for example, recently published a pictorial essay featuring a 12-year-old girl from the countryside, <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhangrong </PERSON>, who dropped out of school to work 12 hours a day in a privately run paper-dye factory. She was shown in photographs carrying a bucket of what was described as noxious, smelly dye on her first day of work. <PERSON> Liaowang </PERSON> and other Chinese reports have expressed alarm at the trend. `` An increasing number of children from rural <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> are missing out on the opportunity to go to school, and the situation is getting worse,'' the official newspaper <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said. Chinese laws state that children under 16 should not work at all. A 1986 law calls for nine years of education, but the government acknowledges this wo n't be possible until the year 2000 because of a lack of facilities. Ironically, the education laws are being ignored in part because of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s much-praised economic reforms. `` The development of the commodity economy has left a deep mark on the hearts of children,'' <PERSON> Liaowang </PERSON> said. `` It is a popular slogan in coastal areas that primary school pupils make big money while college students make little money.'' A <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> survey recently found that only 71 percent of school-age children were attending classes in southern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Guangdong </LOCATION> province, the nation's most advanced in adapting a market-based economy. The People's Daily, which is the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper, reported the inland province of <LOCATION> Hubei </LOCATION> had 1.5 million dropouts last year. The province had about 9 million primary and middle school students in 1985. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> says 96 percent of Chinese children complete the six grades of primary school, but only about two-thirds go on to three-year junior middle school, which is theoretically compulsory. A heavy proportion of the dropouts are girls, who traditionally have received little education in rural <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and are now in demand to work in the thousands of small textile and light industry plants springing up in the countryside. The official Guangming Daily, blaming `` wrong parental attitudes'' for the dropout problem, said an investigation of four construction teams in <LOCATION> Jiangxi </LOCATION> province, southern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, found that nearly a quarter of the workers were children. In <LOCATION> Hebei </LOCATION> province to the north, it added, a third of the peddlers in one village market were junior middle school dropouts. `` My mother told me to quit,'' one 12-year-old candy seller was quoted as saying. It quoted the mother as saying she thought school fees were a waste of money since the boy had little chance of getting a higher education. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has only about 2 million university students, compared to 180 million primary and middle school students out of a population of 1 billion. Although <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> spends a respectable 3 percent of gross national product on education, 20 percent of that goes to higher education. Primary schools, particularly in rural areas, face financial problems that have discouraged school attendance. One report from coastal <LOCATION> Fujian </LOCATION> province said 148 rural schools in one region had been closed and 2,800 pupils had no place to go to school because so many teachers, among the lowest-paid workers in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, had resigned to take other jobs. The Fujian Daily quoted <PERSON> Chen </PERSON> <PERSON> Quanbao </PERSON> as saying he quit his teaching job, which paid 33.5 yuan -LRB- $ 9 -RRB- a month, to make as much in three days selling tea leaves as he did in a semester of teaching. Although schooling is supposed to be free, financially strapped schools have slapped on various maintenance fees. Some poor families say these have forced them to withdraw their children.
</TEXT>
