<HEAD>Actress Dyana Ortelli Avoids Hispanic Stereotypes</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dyana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortelli </PERSON> is perfectly comfortable as the center of attention, which, as it turns out, she usually is. All eyes turn when <PERSON> Ortelli </PERSON>, who stars in the syndicated comedy `` <LOCATION> Marblehead </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Manor </LOCATION>,'' enters a room. She's as hard to miss as a cockatoo in a flock of sparrows. Her dark hair is teased into punk spikes. She is dressed all in black: bolero jacket, bra, miniskirt, boots and gloves. The bra is festooned with multi-hued bows. The gloves are covered with buttons of every size and color. Her fingernails are painted a vivid orange. Her earrings are tiny, multi-colored abacuses. <PERSON> Ortelli </PERSON> laughed. `` I play <PERSON> Lupe </PERSON> on the show, and <PERSON> Lupe </PERSON> is just an extension of myself,'' she said. `` She's the cook, but she's a little weird. Her regular uniform is accessorized by the most colorful things you ever saw. I describe her as a cross between <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> <PERSON> Miranda </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cyndi </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauper </PERSON>. Once, she even wore a hat with bananas in it.'' <PERSON> Ortelli </PERSON>'s 8-year-old son, <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON>, also appeared on the comedy as <PERSON> Lupe </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON>. `` After they signed him, they wanted to change his name to <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>,'' she said. `` I said every other Hispanic on television was named <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>. <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> was really the kind of name <PERSON> Lupe </PERSON> would give her son.'' They also played mother and son in the movies `` Born in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION>'' and `` Three Amigos'' and in a Pepto-Bismol commercial. <PERSON> Ortelli </PERSON> also appeared in `` La Bamba.'' `` Marblehead Manner,'' a farce set in a millionaire's mansion near <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, was part of a five-night package of syndicated comedies <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> ran on its owned-and-operated stations in the half-hour before prime time. The <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> stations did not renew most of the comedies, including `` <LOCATION> Marblehead </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Manor </LOCATION>,'' because of disappointing ratings. The show is syndicated elsewhere and currently in reruns. It also stars <PERSON> Paxton </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitehead </PERSON> as the butler, <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> as the chauffeur, <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> as the handyman, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> as the gardener, and <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorsen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Frazier </PERSON> as the millionaire couple. `` Most of the characters were pretty normal, but <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> was the weirdest,'' she said. `` We were always misinterpreting people and situations. We'd turn things around and create new situations. We were always solving problems that did n't need solving.'' She said the thing she loved about playing <PERSON> Lupe </PERSON> was the freedom she had to make her different from the Hispanic stereotypes. `` She dressed in her own way and she acted in her own way,'' she said. <PERSON> Ortelli </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and grew up in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Her father is an anesthesiologist at a <LOCATION> Laredo </LOCATION> hospital. She attended private schools and as a child was cast in a bilingual children's series in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Her oldest brother danced with the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ballet </LOCATION> and is currently makeup man for the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Opera </LOCATION>. `` When I was in school my first cousin, <PERSON> Paulina </PERSON>, and I made a pact to become actresses, and whoever was successful first would help the other out,'' she said. `` She's doing well in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> as a singer and on a soap opera. She wants to come to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. I wish I had a variety show so I could have her as a guest.'' <PERSON> Ortelli </PERSON> lived in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> for two years while her husband studied abroad. They have since divorced. She moved to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> after returning to this country and was almost immediately cast in the stage play `` Zoot Suit.'' Her maiden name was <PERSON> Elizondo </PERSON> and her married name was <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON>. She combined them to make <PERSON> Ortelli </PERSON>. `` When I came to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> I found out for the first time that I was a member of the Hispanic minority,'' she said. `` My agent said I could play only Hispanic roles and that I had to change my looks to look Hispanic. She said my hair had to be black, straight and parted in the middle. She's no longer my agent. `` My first audition was for the girlfriend of a gang member. My first speaking role on television was as a non-Hispanic nurse on ` <ORGANIZATION> Cagney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Lacey </PERSON>.' I thought sure after they cast me they'd change her name to something Hispanic, but they did n't.'' Her complaint is that Hispanic roles are usually downscale. `` I say get us out of the barrios and into the condos,'' she said. `` I'm not in a position to choose my work. I wish I could. If I'm offered a week's work as a cocaine dealer I'll take it I just ask for a balance. You ca n't expect every Hispanic to be a professional, but you can have a balance.''
</TEXT>
