<HEAD>Pointer Sisters And Lollipops Enliven Computer Biz</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Computer companies face an awful dilemma each time they introduce a new product _ to bore the audience with bits and bytes, or gag it with glitz. This past week, just when cool and dry seemed to be the trend, a pair of multimillion-dollar events showed that computer companies still love show biz. On Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> unveiled two personal computers by filling a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> stage with electronic music and athletic ballet dancers in shiny, multi-colored body suits. A day later, <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced new mid-sized computers with an Academy Awards-style show beamed by satellite to 100,000 people across the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ the biggest such broadcast ever by a private company. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> executive, gamely followed a script that had him receiving a lollipop, a loan approval and a toy soldier's hat from actors portraying grateful <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> customers. At first it seems incongruous for computer makers _ the vanguard of the rational age of high technology _ to be falling back on pyrotechnics and emotional appeals. But then again, people are people, and no one gets a big charge out of hearing someone in a suit drone on about 48-bit addressability or 82385 cache memory controllers. `` We punctuate the straight business message with a little glitter, like the machines rising out of the floor, to make it a little more warm and a little less formal,'' said <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Reisman </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s assistant group executive for the <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. Glitter is second nature to <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION>, which in 1985 hired the Pointer Sisters to dance on a huge model of its Portable 286 singing, `` I'm So Excited.'' Still, the Houston-based computer maker wants to be taken seriously. `` It's not just that we're interested in throwing a party,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Arezzo </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for corporate marketing. `` The bottom line is, you're trying to capture mind space: of the press, the analyst community and most of all your authorized dealers.'' Yes, but how much glitter is too much glitter? `` We've got event-inflation, I think,'' complained <PERSON> Esther </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON>, editor and publisher of Release 1.0 newsletter and a veteran of uncounted product introductions. `` I really hate the ones where they give you 10 minutes of rock music in the dark,'' she said. `` My basic feeling is, if I want to see dancing I'll buy a ticket and go with a date.'' <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, with more than $ 50 billion in annual revenue, must be doing something right. But some people who attend its shows say they have gone from dull to slightly embarrassing. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Machrone </PERSON>, editor-in-chief and publisher of <ORGANIZATION> PC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION>, cringes in memory of an event last year at which <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> executives fumbled through a supposedly impromptu and humorous interchange with <PERSON> Jamie </PERSON> <PERSON> Farr </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON>, the former `` M-A-S-H'' characters. `` It's painful to watch, but <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, I think they think they're really rocking and rolling when they do this,'' <PERSON> Machrone </PERSON> said `` People are afraid to tell them otherwise.'' That's a slightly harsh assessment, said <PERSON> Nora </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gildea </PERSON>, director of marketing for <ORGANIZATION> Ideassociates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Billerica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, a company that does business with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was OK. Everybody sort of laughed wryly in our group You're talking about seasoned customers who've been to a lot of these things.'' <ORGANIZATION> Commodore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> introduced its Amiga three years ago by having <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> take a digitized image of <PERSON> Blondie </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> and use the computer to `` paint'' her picture live on stage at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Lincoln Center <ORGANIZATION> Compaq </ORGANIZATION> once made its chief executive <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Canion </PERSON> appear from nowhere on stage in a blaze of light. It was especially entertaining because <PERSON> Canion </PERSON> is the ultimate straight man. `` I think he sleeps in his suit and tie. So that was a magical moment,'' Ms. <PERSON> Dyson </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has gotten quiet after a run of announcements that included lowering its Apple IIgs from the ceiling into a blaze of lasers and dry ice. Once Apple revved up a sales or dealer meeting with a version of `` Ghostbusters'' featuring dancers in radiation suits, Macintoshes strapped to their backs, singing `` Blue Busters.'' Apple spokeswoman <PERSON> Marlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> has been concentrating lately on networking and communications products that are n't suited to media blitzes. She vows <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> will be back with a splash when the time is right.
