<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 25-26</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Follow Rising Dollar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices danced to the dollar's tune this past week, and the results gave bondholders reason to smile. But what is going to happen when the upbeat music ends? `` The dollar is on a temporary run, and if you want to join the party, you had better belly up to the bar quickly before they quit serving free drinks,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON>, economist for <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. When the dollar stops rising, <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON> said chances increase that bond prices are going to slip and interest rates will edge higher. The dollar climbed sharply this week after the major industrial nations meeting in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> reaffirmed their support for stability of the dollar in foreign-exchange markets. As the dollar rose, foreign investors decided dollar-denominated securities looked even more attractive, and their buying ignited a powerful rally in <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> notes and bonds. On Wednesday, prices of the bellwether 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issue climbed $ 18 for every $ 1,000 in face value while its yield skidded to 8.91 percent from 9.08 percent the previous evening. By midday Friday, prices were up another $ 5 for every $ 1,000 in face value for the week and yields fell to 8.86 percent compared with 9.09 percent at the end of the previous week. But one question facing bond investors at the end of the week was what will happen if the dollar's climb runs out of steam? The analysts say it may force the market to focus again on economic fundamentals. And there is wide disagreement on what the fundamentals show. <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, said he finds evidence of solid growth in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and abroad that will generate gains in inflation to the detriment of bond prices. `` It's my belief that this rally is going to be short-lived and it's not a trend,'' he said. `` Rates will head generally higher with sporadic rallies like this last one creating volatility along the line.'' By the end of the year, <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> expects the 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> will yield about 9.9 percent, or a full percentage point higher than its current level. <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Brusca </PERSON> said he sees some negative signs for the bond market _ industrial production remains strong, factories are operating near full capacity and industrial commodity prices such as aluminum, zinc and nickel are rising. That could push inflation higher, possibly prompting the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> to encourage higher interest rates. He expects the long <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s yield will rise to 9.75 percent before settling down to about 9.5 percent at the end of the year. But <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON>, chief economist for <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bancorporation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, said he finds mixed evidence on the strength of the economy in the latest economic reports, and expects a slowdown is imminent. This past week, for instance, the government reported a 2.2 percent decline in durable goods orders for May and said the economy grew at a 3.6 percent rate in the first quarter after adjustment for inflation, down from its 3.9 percent growth estimate a month earlier. <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> said he expects long-term rates to fall to 8.75 percent by the end of the year and 8 percent by the middle of 1989 as a reduction in capital spending leads to a broader economic slowdown. <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON>, research director for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Jenrette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, is even more optimistic about chances for lower rates. He said he thinks a moderation in economic growth over the next few months will send long-term rates to the 8 percent to 8.25 percent range by fall. <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> worries about the impact that the drought may have on the economy, but it is n't the concern you might expect. While he expects the drought to push food prices higher, he does n't think the increase will add much to overall inflation. <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> is more concerned about the psychological damage that higher food prices may have on consumers' willingness to spend, a key factor in keeping the economy growing. `` Once they see food prices increase, we may have a break in consumer confidence,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions June 25-26</NOTE>
