<HEAD>Personal Income, Spending Up Modestly in May</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The consumer spending boom could slow this summer, some economists said after the government reported a modest increase in personal spending and personal income for the month of May. A rise in the dollar on Friday helped the bond market, but stocks slipped. Most grain prices retreated in response to scattered showers, while energy futures prices dropped. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 5.33 points to 2,142.96, finishing the week with a gain of nearly 2 percent. The dollar's rise carried it past key psychological resistance points to levels against many major currencies not seen in eight months. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar rose to 130.53 Japanese yen from 128.62 yen on Thursday. The dollar rose to 1.8155 West German marks from 1.7850 late Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that personal income rose 0.3 percent last month following a 0.1 percent gain in April. Meanwhile, personal consumption expenditures, which include virtually everything except interest on debt, rose a moderate 0.5 percent in May following a 0.4 percent increase in April. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagens </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, consulting firm, said, `` I think basically our biggest concern is how weak consumer spending is. ... The income growth is simply not there to support much growth, particularly given higher food prices expected because of the drought,'' he said. Through the first five years of the six-year economic expansion, consumer buying has fueled the growth. Now, analysts are looking for exports and sale of equipment to businesses to drive the economy. Americans' disposable income _ what they have left after paying taxes _ shot up 1.5 percent in May, after a 1.0 percent drop in April that was the largest decline in a year. The drought-driven rally in most grain and soybean futures markets stalled as scattered showers forced skittish traders to pause for a look at reality, analysts said. Prices yo-yoed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> but finished mixed with only oat futures continuing the sharply higher trend established earlier in the week. On other exchanges, precious metals futures fell sharply; livestock and meat futures were mixed; energy futures slipped; and stock-index futures retreated. `` This thing has more lives than a cat. It kept coming back and coming back,'' <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said of the grain market's erratic performance.
</TEXT>
